column7: Project success starts with bulletproof user research—learn the essential methods in lesson 2 of "Personas and User Research: Design Products and Services People Need and Want"
column9:
Hi Candace,

Ready to create personas that work? It all starts with user research. 

In lesson 2, you'll discover proven methods to truly understand your users—so you can design products, services, and experiences they’ll love—not just tolerate. 

Then roll up your sleeves for the project activity, where you’ll get access to real user research and, if you want, even conduct your own!

Your instructor, usability expert William Hudson, is waiting for you here:
https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

Here's what's coming:

- Grounded theory for qualitative research.
- Why user observations beat interviews.
- Quantitative research for personas.
- Introduction to affinity diagramming.

You’ll apply all of this to a project you choose, or you can use ours. It's your call. Either way, this activity will take you another step towards exciting job opportunities and higher salaries.

Don't forget we release one lesson per week based on the following schedule:

--- Course schedule ---
Available now: Welcome and Introduction
Available now: Personas: Why They Work and What People Get Wrong
Available now: User Research for Personas: How to Truly Understand Your Users
Aug 12th, 2025: Affinity Diagrams: How to Find Patterns That Shape Effective Personas
Aug 19th, 2025: How to Build Personas That Give Focus and Get Used
Aug 26th, 2025: Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up

Happy learning by doing!

PS: You’ll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

William Hudson
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column2: CUNY SPS - Office of Student Services
column7: Complete SPARC by September 9
column9:
Hello Candace,I am writing to inform you to about an important online training program, the Sexual and Interpersonal Violence Prevention and Response Course (SPARC), which you must complete no later than September 9 in order to register for Winter Session and Spring Semester 2026 classes when registration opens in October. 

New York State's Enough is Enough (EIE) statute requires that all NYS colleges provide students with ongoing education and training about sexual misconduct, including domestic violence, dating violence, stalking, sexual harassment, gender-based harassment, and sexual violence. CUNY has implemented SPARC to provide students with this training. While the University encourages all newly admitted students to complete SPARC, students who have completed the training at another CUNY campus are not required to repeat it SPS.

To access SPARC, log into Brightspace and locate SPS Student SPARC Training Fall 2025 under My Courses. SPARC should take about 30 minutes to complete. Please note that non-completion will prevent registration for future terms.

For more information about SPARC, please review the detailed instructions and answers to frequently asked questions <https://files.constantcontact.com/92072faa701/90136dd8-0987-44bb-811c-40fb22bb49ff.pdf>. If you require addition information or support, kindly send an email message describing the issue to SPARC@sps.cuny.edu. Please be sure to include your full name and 8-digit EMPLID student identification number in all SPARC-related communications.

You may also visit the CUNY SPS website <http://www1.cuny.edu/sites/title-ix/campus/cuny-school-of-professional-studies/> for additional information about the University's efforts to combat sexual misconduct.

Thank you.


Christopher Leydon <mailto:SPARC@sps.cuny.edu?subject=SPS%20Students%20SPARC%20Spring%202023>

    Student Title IX Coordinator 
The CUNY School of Professional Studies is regionally accredited through the Middle States Commission on Higher Education.119 West 31st Street | New York, NY 10001



This email was sent to aicoaching2025@gmail.com by CUNY SPS - Office of Student Services.
Unsubscribe from CUNY School of Professional Studies. <https://engage.sps.cuny.edu/go?r=optout&mid=2db62101-2fa0-4b82-ac60-12631eeb4d49>

column7: Update on Community Boot camp Removal and TrustPilot Review offer
column9:
DATAEXPERT.IO COMMUNITY ACADEMY
You're receiving this email from DataExpert.io Community Academy.


 * Some students are saying that I'm intentionally biasing the reviews on
   TrustPilot which feels unethical. Initially, I felt defensive and frustrated
   by this. But after sleeping on it, I realized the 4 one star reviews are
   right even if the 600 5 star ones feel good.,

column7: The final lesson “Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up” is now ready in your course “Build a Standout UX/UI Portfolio: Land Your Dream Job”
column9:
Great news, Candace, the final wrap-up lesson of the course is now available!

Well done for making it this far. We hope you’re on your way to creating a portfolio that you’re proud of.  

We’re happy that 6,989 course-takers have joined our class so far, some of whom have scored more than 70% overall. If you’ve completed the course and earned your Course Certificate, remember to download and display it on your LinkedIn profile, portfolio and resume along with your unique link so recruiters can verify its authenticity. 

Take the final lesson and start generating your Course Certificate here: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/build-a-standout-ux-ui-portfolio-land-your-dream-job 

Don’t worry if you haven’t completed the course. After all, this course (and all other courses from the Interaction Design Foundation) are created for busy people, and you’ll have access to it for as long as you’re a member. Take your time and learn at your own pace—slow and steady wins the race. 

We hope you feel confident and ready to present your new and improved portfolio. Have you enjoyed the course? Do you have any feedback for us—positive or otherwise? Please remember to respond to our course feedback, which you can find in the final lesson: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/build-a-standout-ux-ui-portfolio-land-your-dream-job 

 

-------- Current Leaderboard --------
Please note that the leaderboard may change since some questions have not been graded yet.

--- Top Learners in United States ---

1. Vittorio Villella, UX Designer Developer Lead
2. Ipsita Chatterjea, Executive Director
3. Alyson Kim

--- Top Learners in North America ---

1. Mahdad Mansouri, ui/ux designer
2. Santiago Gaspar Hernandez Salazar, Product Designer
3. Carlos Garcia, Associate Quality Designer

--- Top Learners Worldwide ---

1. Yasaman Sharifpour, Product Designer
2. Mahdad Mansouri, ui/ux designer
3. Abhishek Gupta, Chief Marketing Manager (UX -UI Design)
 

 

PS: You’ll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

Morgane Peng
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column7: A closer look at reMarkable Paper Pro Move
Master personas. Make better products, services, and experiences. Candace, lesson 4 awaits.
column9:
Hi Candace,

It’s time to bring your persona to life!

In this final lesson, you’ll home in on personas as the guiding light of your user-centered design process—and discover why keeping them simple leads to better, faster decisions for you and your team.

To top it off, you’ll build a persona fueled by the insights from your affinity diagram, ready to shine in your portfolio.

Raring to take the leap into persona-driven design? Get started at:
https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

Here's what's in store:
- How to build personas and promote them.
- Minimum viable personas.
- The psychology of personas.
- Personas, abilities, and skills.
- Primary vs secondary personas.
- How many personas.
- Personas for research participant recruitment.
- The next steps.

And for the grand finale, your new skills and insights will come together as you craft a persona that transforms user needs into a clear, actionable picture.

Master personas, upgrade your design game, and take your career to the next level. Let’s go!

PS: You’ll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

William Hudson
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column7: Bring your portfolio to life in 4 of “Build a Standout UX/UI Portfolio: Land Your Dream Job”
column9:
Hi Candace, 

Welcome back to your design portfolio journey! In the last lesson, you honed your skills in developing engaging case studies. 

It's time to take your design portfolio to the next level by putting it all together and adding those final touches and flourishes. In lesson 4, you’ll finalize your new and improved portfolio. 

Jump in right now at: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/build-a-standout-ux-ui-portfolio-land-your-dream-job 

You'll discover: 

The best tools to use for maximum impact. 

Techniques to craft an outstanding landing page that grabs attention. 

Strategies to elevate your portfolio with those extra-special finishing touches. 

Pro tips on presenting your portfolio to potential employers with confidence. 

Our expert instructor, Design Director at Societe Generale CIB Morgane Peng, will guide you through practical examples to ensure that you effectively grasp these concepts. Plus, you'll continue with the portfolio exercise from the last lesson and put your newfound knowledge into practice. 

Let's get into it and elevate your design portfolio to new heights! 

We’ll release one lesson per week based on the schedule below: 

--- Course schedule ---
Available now: Welcome and Introduction
Available now: Attract Success: Your Portfolio is the Key to Design Your Dream Career
Available now: Hook Hiring Managers' Attention with Your Design Portfolio
Available now: How to Make Your Case Studies Stand Out and Tell Your Story
Available now: Land Your Dream Job with a Standout Portfolio
Aug 20th, 2025: Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up 

 

Happy learning! 

PS: You’ll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

Morgane Peng
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column7: Lovable Update - agent mode, analytics, business plan & more
column9:
Lovable Logo

******************
Lovable Update —
Aug 2025
******************

Hey hey - we've got a lot of (pretty big) updates for you. Here’s everything we shipped to Lovable in past few weeks:

----------------------------------
Agent Mode is the new default mode
----------------------------------

image

With this upgrade, Lovable becomes a truly agentic partner—interpreting requests, understanding your codebase, fixing issues, executing complex multi-step edits across files, integrating with external tools, and reducing errors by 91%, so you can build more ambitious apps faster and with less friction.

Legacy mode (where you don’t use agent) will be sunsetting on September 1, 2025.

----------------------------------------
Real-time analytics on your Lovable apps
----------------------------------------

image

Curious how your app is performing in the wild?
You can now track live traffic and engagement directly inside Lovable including:

* Visitors: How many people are using your app
Pageviews: Which pages get the most attention
* Visit duration: How long users stay
* Bounce rate: What percentage leaves instantly
* Views per visit: How deeply users engage
The data updates in near real-time so you can spot trends, debug issues, or just celebrate your first users! Available now under Project Settings → Analytics

----------------------------------
Pricing change coming to chat mode
----------------------------------

Pricing for chat mode is moving from 1 credit per message to dynamic pricing, which matches the pricing model for agent mode. This means that each message and response cost is based on the complexity of the message; so some messages and responses cost less than 1 credit, and some, if quite complex, cost more. This change will be rolling out to all users on September 1, 2025.

---------------------
Lovable Business Plan
---------------------

Introducing the Lovable Business Plan, built for teams that need more control, privacy, and flexibility. It includes everything in Pro, plus powerful upgrades:

* SSO for secure org-wide sign-in
* Personal projects only visible to you
* Templates for consistent styling
* Yearly plans now available
You can now switch to a yearly subscription for any paid Lovable plan. Get a discounted rate, simplify billing, and worry less about monthly renewals.

---------------
Visual Edits v2
---------------

We have refined the visual edits experience after tons of feedback. More responsive, precise, and delightful to use. It’s faster than ever to tweak your UI, fix copy, or adjust layout—without leaving the live preview.

You can also jump to selected elements in code when using visual edits, tightens the loop between design and implementation.

------------------------
Project Invites Workflow
------------------------

Invited users must now formally accept or decline access to a project—both from email and magic links. This avoids stale “pending” members and improves collaborator tracking.

-----------------------------------
Search all files in the code editor
-----------------------------------

Use the file search inside the code editor to quickly locate code and add file paths directly into chat.

-------------------
Unified Credits Bar
-------------------

image

We’ve shipped a new credits bar that combines all credit types into one clean, unified view—no more jumping between different displays to track usage.

-------------------
Upgraded People Tab
-------------------

The People
tab in workspace settings has been redesigned. It now includes pagination (20 users per page), search, and filtering by member status—making it much easier to manage large teams.

--------------------------
Scales to large workspaces
--------------------------

Thanks to backend improvements, we now support massive workspaces with tens of thousands of members without performance issues.

-----------------------
Published project badge
-----------------------

image

We’ve added a small but useful touch: all published projects now display a “Published” badge so it’s easier to see what’s live at a glance.

Bug fixes

* Fixed image upload bug causing >1% of initial generations to fail if the user wasn’t logged in.
* Prevents redundant updates when a project is already up to date with the deployed version.
* You can now disconnect a project from legacy Supabase when disconnecting the org.
* Reconnecting orgs with invalid tokens is now seamless.
Hope you like these improvements, let
us know what you think!

Start Building Now ( https://lovable.dev )

Best,
The Lovable Team

Lovable Logo

Turn ideas into Lovable products at
Lovable.dev ( https://lovable.dev )

Unsubscribe ( http://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgTmjgoDAM-wyQTOsMkEAZiZj_nELSso12QDCbNS3A== )

column7: If You’re Still Struggling With Imposter Syndrome, Read This
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’re doing well 🙌

Last week I wrote about the Batman Effect and I wanted to
continue along a similar theme today by talking about imposter
syndrome.

And I know I’ve talked about imposter syndrome quite a bit before
but it’s probably the most common obstacle that I've seen that's
holding back aspiring creators and entrepreneurs from making
progress towards their ambitions and goals. Whether it’s making
progress on their YouTube channel, if they’re a member of PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/6qhehoullp59e7i9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWltcG9zdGVyXzgmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
), or looking to take their first steps on the path to building
their business in the $1k Challenge, the core feeling, or fear,
is the same.

And I totally get it. In fact, I remember having to confront all
these inner questions about my self-worth and expertise back when
I recorded my first ever YouTube video, and tbh, I still
experience imposter syndrome even today with over 6 million
subscribers.

I’ll be working on a script thinking “is this even valuable?” or
“who am I to be talking about starting a business when there are
people that’ve made way more money than me?” - these feelings of
self-doubt never fully go away and they’ll be with you at every
stage of your YouTube journey.

And that’s why I’m keen to write about this whole topic on a
regular basis - to remind everyone reading this that you’re not
alone if you’re experiencing those feelings whether it’s starting
a channel or a business.

But the thing is, when you step outside your comfort zone and put
yourself out there in any capacity on the internet, you get this
massive psychological unlock. You’ll realise that all those
catastrophic stories you’d made up in your head just weren’t
true, and this mental breakthrough is genuinely life-changing.

Plus, if you’re waiting for imposter syndrome to disappear before
you start your channel - you’ll end up waiting forever. So you
need to start despite the feeling, not after it magically goes
away.

And this actually reminds me of something Tim Runia (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/kkhmh2unn85xvnik/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQFRpbVJ1bmlhL2ZlYXR1cmVk
) spoke about during his session with our $1K Challenge students
a few weeks ago.

Tim’s a filmmaker from the Netherlands who’s been obsessed with
creating videos since he was a kid. He even ran a video
production agency with a friend for 7 years, so on paper, he had
all the credentials and skills to succeed on YouTube.

But despite all that experience, Tim delayed starting his channel
for 5 whole years because he was held back by all the same
feelings - self-doubt, procrastination, and that nagging voice
saying “maybe I’m not ready yet.”

After taking the leap to go all-in on YouTube, his channel’s now
growing pretty quickly and he’s building a creator business that
many of you who read these emails want for yourself too.

So I’d love to share a clip from this recording with you, where
he not only talks about how he overcame his imposter syndrome
around publishing videos on YouTube, but also around the
terrifying prospect of actually selling a digital product to his
audience in exchange for real money.

​You can watch the clip here. (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/58hvh8ugg5n62ki7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2hvdy10by1kZWFsLXdpdGgtaW1wb3N0ZXItc3luZHJvbWUv
)​

Hopefully this gives you the nudge to finally hit record or press
publish on your first video, and if you do end up posting it, hit
reply and let me know - I’d love to hear about it.

And as a reminder, if you’re a beginner looking to take that
first step, then do check out the 7 Video Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/25h2h9u3378mwdb8/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249aW1wb3N0ZXJfOCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

But if you’re looking for our complete YouTube package that gives
you access to a community of like-minded creators for
accountability and access to monthly workshops for inspiration
(we’ve actually got productivity expert and YouTuber, Jeff Su,
delivering a presentation tomorrow 👀) then you can sign up for
the Part Time YouTuber Academy here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/6qhehoullp59e7i9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWltcG9zdGVyXzgmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

Otherwise have a great week and we’ll talk soon :)

Ali xx

P.S. Tim made an absolutely incredible video documenting the
start of his YouTube journey and overcoming all these limiting
beliefs. It’s called Living your dream is easier than you think
and it’s definitely worth checking out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/qvh8h8udd84kpqfg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD0zMTdzJnY9bC1NdDVPV3NQam8=
) 👀

🚀 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhx6x89nt6h62qxkggclhgvoew/g3hnhwummelqwgt3/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
).

Update Your Email Preferences (

your services at Hostinger. The new version will take effect on September 9,
2025.

of the highlights:  1. Digital Services Act (section 11): There’s an improved section that explains

Anna Watts for The New York TimesCHARLIE KIRK, RIGHT-WING INFLUENCER, SHOT AT
EVENT IN UTAH
The head of Turning Point USA, a conservative youth organization, was shot in
the neck while he was speaking at a campus event at Utah Valley University. His
condition was not immediately known.

column7: Is this goodbye 😢? Checking in one last time
column9:
Weglot ( https://www.weglot.com/ )

Hi Candace,

I wanted to check in with you one last time to see if you’re still interested in trying out Weglot. If now’s not the right time, we’re sorry to see you go!

But, we’re always here for when the time comes and you’re ready to go multilingual.

If of course there’s another reason why we couldn’t help make your multilingual website dreams come true, we’d love to have your honest feedback.

Hit reply to this email and let us know if there’s anything at all that we could change and do better in the hope of welcoming you back!

Have a great day,
Christophe, Head of Support at Weglot

Weglot

7 Cite Paradis,
Paris, France

YouTube ( https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCrRhoQnfz-1aJ9awyHxEsOg )

column7: [PythonAnywhere] How about editing some files?
column9:
Hi there,

Did you know that you can use PythonAnywhere to edit Python scripts as files,
as well as just running code in an interactive Console?

Head on over to the "Files" tab on your dashboard, where you'll find a file
browser just like the one on your computer.  You can:

* Create a brand new file, giving it a name that ends in .py

* Or, upload a Python file from your own PC

And then you'll be able to edit it in our built-in Python editor.  It has a few
features to help you, like syntax-highlighting, and automatic checking for
common errors.

https://www.pythonanywhere.com/user/jabjabcarnival/files/home/jabjabcarnival/

You can also hit the Run Button (>>>) and see your Python code run right there,
beneath the editor

Take a look at the "Keyboard Shortcuts" menu for more features.  Sublime
Text fans will appreciate multiple cursors for example :)


Happy coding!


Piotr + the PythonAnywhere team.


Piotr Kaznowski
Developer

PS These emails are designed to help you get the most out of PythonAnywhere,
including pointing you towards some cool features that are a bit hidden.
We'll only send out one a week, but if you want to unsubscribe from them,
you can do so here:
https://www.pythonanywhere.com/unsubscribe_from/engagement_emails/?email=aicoaching2025%40gmail.com&n=e640d807aa143f1e677409405986fb27

column7: 👀 Why You Should Be Thinking More About Your Hook
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’re having a good day so far.

Quick reminder before we dive into today’s email: there are less
than 48hrs left to sign up to the $1K Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/wnh2h6uqoo688rbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1ob29rc18zMCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
) which starts on Friday (August 1st). If you’ve been thinking
about taking your first steps towards making money online and
learning the foundational skills for financial freedom, you can
get more info and sign up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/wnh2h6uqoo688rbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1ob29rc18zMCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

Anyway, a few weeks back, we wrapped up a fantastic workshop with
George Blackman (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/reh8h9um55znn0s6/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ2VvcmdlYmxhY2ttYW4uY29tLw==
) - one of the top scriptwriting consultants in the space - all
about the importance of writing quality YouTube hooks and
systemising the whole process, because let’s be honest, it can be
one of the most challenging (and dare I say stressful 😅) parts of
creating a YouTube video.

You’ve heard me talk endlessly about the importance of packaging
as it relates to thumbnails and titles but internally we actually
talk about TTH when we’re talking about packaging and that stands
for - Title, Thumbnail and Hook. I’m not actually sure when we
started using that TTH acronym but it’s the thing we think about
before anything else as it relates to creating a video.

Yes, the title and the thumbnail are crucial, but if the first
10-30 seconds don’t provide the payoff that the viewer was
expecting after clicking on the video, they’ll move on, you’ll
miss out on watch time and it’s unlikely that the video will
perform. So focusing most of your effort on creating a strong
hook really does have outsized returns when it comes to preparing
your video.

And that’s why we asked George to come back to give a workshop
that concentrated on that first section of your video and having
worked with creators like Colin & Samir, Mike Shake and others,
he definitely knows his stuff when it comes to writing and
optimising video hooks.

Anyway, I wanted to share a clip from his session where he breaks
down the three biggest traps most creators fall into when writing
hooks and more importantly, how to avoid them.

You can watch the clip here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/08hwhgu277rqq2fp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL21pc3Rha2VzLXBlb3BsZS1tYWtlLXdyaXRpbmctaG9va3M_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWhvb2tfMzAmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

I hope you find it useful and remember you can get access to this
entire session as well as the previous scriptwriting session that
George delivered during CreatorWeek plus over 50 more guest
workshops from the past few years by signing up to the Part-Time
YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/8ghqh3uo55nkkqul/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWhvb2tfMzAmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

Finally, I’d love to hear from you about what you’re currently
struggling with as it relates to YouTube and content creation.
Whether you’re just starting out, or growing or trying to
monetise your channel, I’m keen to hear what’s your biggest pain
point at the moment - just hit reply and let me know and I’ll try
to address them over the coming weeks and months in these emails.
I always enjoy writing creator-based content here or sharing
content that I hope will be helpful but it’s really useful to
know what the most common issues are so let me know :)

Have a great rest of the week!

Speak soon!

Ali xx

🚀 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/mvu2vm8x35t5hqo529rhmhrn9m0qqi3h5de26/vqh3hmuokkr88giw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
).

Davidoff Studios/Getty ImagesCONGRESS OBTAINS DRAWING FOR EPSTEIN APPARENTLY
SIGNED BY TRUMP
Democrats on the House Oversight Committee released an image of the sexually
suggestive drawing apparently signed by President Trump for a book celebrating
Jeffrey Epstein’s 50th birthday. Trump has insisted he never wrote such a note.

column7: From "I'll Never Get This" to "I Built That" in 8 Weeks Flat
column9:
When I asked 12,168 Python beginners to describe their biggest struggle with coding, one response stopped me cold:

> "I feel like I'm stuck learning syntax for 5 years."

Another person wrote, "I know some concepts, but I never *build* anything!"

And perhaps most heartbreaking:

> "[Two years] in, I can code the basics of Python loops, if statements, functions. I feel like I don't really know anything on a deeper level."

These aren't isolated frustrations.

They're symptoms of a fundamental problem with how Python is taught. The traditional approach treats programming like a foreign language class:

Memorize the vocabulary.
Study the grammar. Practice the conjugations.

But coding isn't about
memorization.

It's about thinking differently: It's the difference between knowing the words "hammer," "nail," and "wood" versus actually building a house.

I call it the Builder's Gap:

That gaping canyon between "following tutorials" and "creating from scratch", between understanding pieces and seeing the whole picture.

It's where many learners stall: watching their 197th tutorial, convinced that this next one will finally make everything click.

But it never does.

You see, the problem isn't the tutorials. The problem is that scattered facts, without a framework to connect them, don't magically turn into real-world coding ability.

Even the best tutorials (ours included) work 10× better when you code alongside an expert who catches your mistakes in real-time.

Think about where you are right now.

Maybe you're stuck in "Tutorial Hell":
you can follow along perfectly when someone else is coding, but face a blank file and you freeze.

Or perhaps you're drowning in "Syntax Quicksand," where every coding session becomes a memory test.

Was it append() or add()...?
Brackets or parentheses...?

Or maybe you've reached the most frustrating stage of all:

You understand what code does when you read it, you can even modify existing programs, but writing something from nothing?

Your brain just doesn't work that way.

You know the theory but struggle to apply it. You understand the concepts but choke when you try to build anything.

Here's the thing: You're not alone.

In over ten years of running Real Python and teaching millions of developers, we learned that crossing the Builder's Gap is the #1 reason why beginners quit.

Because real skill requires structured progression, guided practice, and most
importantly, immediate feedback when you're doing something wrong.

That's exactly what you get from our Python for Beginners cohort course. ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners/ )

Our team of Python educators analyzed thousands of responses from real beginners to understand exactly where learners get stuck and why.

As a result, every week of this program is designed to solve a specific problem that actual beginners face.

We carefully developed it to give you the clarity, structure, and practice you need to go from zero experience to writing your own Python applications with rock-solid confidence.

In just eight weeks, you'll master the core building blocks of Python.

Variables, data structures, control flow, functions, and object-oriented programming (OOP). You won't just watch someone else
code. You'll get hands-on, guided practice every step of the way.

No more wondering if you're "cut out for coding..." Instead, you'll have undeniable proof in the programs you built.

This isn't just another online course. It's an immersive eight-week transformation where you'll join a small group of committed learners, get live guidance from an exceptional teacher, and build real projects that prove you can do this.

You'll finish with several working programs in your portfolio, a network of fellow programmers, and most importantly, the confidence and skills to keep growing on your own.

By the end of the program, you won't just know Python—
you'll think like a programmer.

You'll see problems and immediately understand how to break them down into code. You'll build programs from scratch without needing tutorials. You'll debug errors in minutes instead of hours.

And,
most importantly, you'll have crossed that gap from "I'm learning Python" to "I build things with Python."

The investment is straightforward: eight weeks of your time and commitment, and the willingness to code along, make mistakes, and ask questions when you're stuck.

In return, you'll cross the Builder's Gap and transform from someone who watches programming to someone who does programming.

Decision time:

Every day you wait is another day stuck in Tutorial Hell. Another day watching others build while you watch. Another day closer to giving up on coding altogether.

This cohort starts October 13th. That's it. Miss this date and you're looking at some time in 2026. That's another 3-6 months of spinning your wheels.

Availability for this cohort is limited and 50% of the available seats are already taken, so don't miss out. Claim your spot at the link below:

➡ View the Full Syllabus and Reserve Your Spot ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners/ )

— Dan Bader

To make sure you keep getting these emails, please add info@realpython.com to your address book or allowlist. Want out of the loop? Unsubscribe ( https://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgSUzQcDAKymeaumeQGZmwpybW9AZ4djMfxpjfA= )

$100,000 LOVABLE SHIPPED DEMO DAY

 

Hey friends of lovable,

 

Lovable is giving $100k to the winner of shipped demo day

 

Over the past 6 weeks thousands of builders have been participating in lovable shipped ( https://shipped.lovable.app/ ). This program was designed to equip as many potential founders as possible with the skills necessary to take their ideas through to a launched product.

 

We brought in over 20 expert speakers such as Christian Peverelli, Claire Vo, Harry Roper and many more on our weekly livestreams ( https://www.youtube.com/@lovable-labs/streams ).

 

We've also given away over $30k in builders grants and giveaways to our founders as well as access to millions in perks/discounts through our partners. 

 

This Wednesday Aug 6th, the top 10 participants of the lovable shipped pre accelerator will be pitching live before a panel of VC's for their chance at a $100k grant. 

 

You can see some of the project submissions showcased here: shipped showcase ( https://preview--s1-showcase.lovable.app/ )

 

Achievements

 

Lovable shipped had over 5,800 applications across 95 countries with participants aged from 9 to 75.

 

During the course of the program over 465k in revenue was generated across 80k+ active users of these apps and over 50 projects secured investments. 

 

So tune in to watch the inaugural season finale of lovable shipped this week.

 

When

 

Aug 6th at 6:30pm (CEST) or 9:30am (PST)

 

Where

 

Register here https://lu.ma/ype8fy6l

Questions?

 

You can find more information in the Shipped Season 1 official rules ( https://shipped.lovable.app/season1rules ). This is just the beginning, more to come for the next season of Lovable Shipped. 

 

Looking forward to seeing you support our founders at the livestream this week,

 

Lovable Shipped team

column7: Why I Wear Fake Glasses In My YouTube Videos
column9:
Hey Candace,

Before we get started with this email, I just wanted to let you
know that my team and I are building an online business school
for lifestyle business entrepreneurs, called the Lifestyle
Business Academy. If you’re interested, you can click here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvowxrgughv2xemlls9hplqro/3ohphdu336x753hp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVzdHlsZS1idXNpbmVzcy1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1nbGFzc2VzXzAxJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) to find out more.

Anyway, in today’s email I wanted to talk about something called
the “Batman effect” - and no, this isn’t about fighting crime in
Gotham 😅

One of the biggest reasons so many people never get started on
YouTube, including lots of our PTYA (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvowxrgughv2xemlls9hplqro/48hvh7ummzwrdgcq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWJhdG1hbl8xJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) students, is because they’re paralysed by the fear of
publishing their first video, and that’s where the Batman effect
comes in. It’s essentially a way to push past your fears by
imagining yourself as someone else - someone braver and more
confident than you feel right now.

The two classic examples of this are Beyoncé, who channeled her
assertive and empowered alter ego “Sasha Fierce” to feel more
confident when performing, and Adele, whose stage persona was
“Sasha Carter” (an amalgamation of Beyoncé’s Sasha Fierce and
country singer June Carter) to help her overcome stage fright.

And there’s actually a whole bunch of science behind the Batman
effect.

Adopting an alter ego is basically an extreme form of
“self-distancing” - a psychological trick that involves stepping
back from your immediate feelings to view a situation more
objectively and take control of your fear and anxiety.

Back in 2017, researchers (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvowxrgughv2xemlls9hplqro/wnh2h6uqq9mw28hl/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWVwYmx1ZS5saWIudW1pY2guZWR1L2JpdHN0cmVhbS9oYW5kbGUvMjAyNy40Mi8xMzgzMzYvY2RldjEyNjk1LnBkZj9pc0FsbG93ZWQ9eSZzZXF1ZW5jZT0x
) took a bunch of kids and gave them a boring task to complete,
telling them they’d be “good helpers” if they worked on it for as
long as possible instead of switching to play games on an iPad.

And the results showed that kids who imagined themselves as a
character, like Batman or Dora the Explorer, performed way better
on the boring task compared to those who just thought about it
from their own perspective or talked about themselves in third
person. They also enjoyed it more too.

I actually used the Batman effect back in my early YouTube days.
Even though I had laser eye surgery and didn’t need glasses
anymore, I kept wearing these fake glasses whenever I was on
camera or giving talks.

Why? Because when I put on those glasses, I wasn’t nervous Ali
worried about messing up and thinking “what will people think of
me?” - instead, I stepped into the mindset of young Professor X
from the X-Men series.

He’s this brilliant teacher who’s amazing at explaining complex
concepts, genuinely cares about his students, and happens to have
telepathic powers (which is pretty cool I can’t lie), so my
glasses helped me focus on sharing valuable knowledge in the best
way possible to help people watching.

I don’t often find myself wearing these fake glasses anymore, and
that’s another fascinating thing about the Batman effect - over
time, those confident qualities you’re channeling often become
part of who you actually are, so the alter ego becomes less
necessary as you grow into that new version of yourself.

If you’re stuck and haven’t yet published that first video, try
asking yourself “who would I be if I wasn’t afraid?” Pick a
specific character that you admire and you’ll be surprised how
much easier filming becomes when you step into their shoes.

And if you want to overcome your initial fears and learn how to
create videos all while being part of a supportive community of
fellow creators, I created the 7 Video Challenge (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvowxrgughv2xemlls9hplqro/reh8h9umm9k0lka6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YmF0bWFuXzEmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) as a way to reward you for taking action. It’s been
game-changing for previous students, and if you want to find out
what that reward is, you can check it out here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvowxrgughv2xemlls9hplqro/reh8h9umm9k0lka6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YmF0bWFuXzEmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

Talk soon,

Ali xx

column7: 3 Reminders to Myself...
column9:
Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - last month I mentioned that we’d
just launched our second app, Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/p8hehqu44g6q0mar/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2xpZmVub3Rlcy8xMg==
), and we’ve had some great feedback so far. We've continued to
make improvements over the last month so if you’ve not checked it
out yet, you can download it here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/p8hehqu44g6q0mar/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2xpZmVub3Rlcy8xMg==
). (And if you’re waiting for the Android version, we’re hoping
to launch that in the next couple of weeks - appreciate the
patience 🙏)

Anyway, on with the newsletter. I’m back in Hong Kong this week
after a nice team off-site in Bali where the 14 of us hung out in
a lovely villa, did some business planning stuff, did some
excursions and dinners etc. Great vibes all round. Except on the
last day, where I got struck with food poisoning and ended up bed
bound with fevers and lots of trips to the toilet.

Thankfully, Izzy and I had booked a few extra days in Bali at a
nice hotel at the end of the team offsite, so I was able to use
that time to recover. And tbh it was kinda nice lying in bed all
day reading more Harry Potter Fan Fiction - just finished book 2
of The Arithmancer trilogy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/x0hph3uee92q62tg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlb2ZvdXJvd24ub3JnL3dvcmtzLzE0MjgxNDQwP3ZpZXdfZnVsbF93b3JrPXRydWU=
), set in an alternate universe where Hermione’s an absolute
legend at maths, and so ends up becoming a next-level Arithmancer
able to create spells, understand how magic works etc. It’s
great.

Anyway, in this issue of LifeNotes, I wanted to share a few notes
to myself - reminders of lessons I’ve learned (or re-learned) in
the last few weeks that I’m hoping to actually stick to.

1 - Nothing good comes from staying up late. The only
circumstance in which it’s nice is when we’ve got friends over
for dinner, and the vibes are great, and we want to keep the
party going for a bit longer. That’s acceptable. But for
literally everything else - it’s just not worth it. The extra
hour of work being squeezed out at 10pm - not worth it. The extra
hour of scrolling on Instagram or watching random YouTube videos
- obviously not worth it. Even staying up engrossed in a book
beyond 10:30pm - not worth it. An early night = more refreshed
and energised the next day, across literally every measure. It
shows up in the various health-tracking scores: sleep, recovery,
stress. And more importantly, it shows up in our mood and energy
levels. So for goodness sake - stop staying up past 10:30pm. Go
to bed at a reasonable hour, read on Kindle in bed (nothing too
exciting though), and wake up feeling amazing the next day.

2 - On the work front, there’s no need to be in such a rush.
We’re planning to do this for decades. Whether we launch the
thing this week or next week, or even next month, makes literally
no difference in the grand scheme of things. So remember that the
most important goal is to be able to continue playing the
infinite game, and to continue enjoying it. The biggest threat to
the business isn’t that we didn’t launch product X early enough.
It’ll be if we stop enjoying the game of it, and then want to
quit and do something else. Optimise for sustainability and fun.

3 - At this stage, improvements in our subjective well-being (or
“happiness”) won’t come from external stuff. We’ve already won
the external stuff game. The journey to focus on now is the
internal journey. Being at peace with where we’re at, immersing
ourselves in the present moment, staying open and expansive
rather than closed and contractive. Everything’s unfolding
exactly as it’s supposed to, so there’s never any reason to worry
about anything at all.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

-----------------------------------------------------------------
​80,000 Hours: Find Careers with Real Impact (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/6qhehoullnr9geu9/aHR0cHM6Ly84MDAwMGhvdXJzLm9yZy9nZXR0aGVndWlkZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTIwMjUtODBLTUFSLWFsaS1hYmRhYWwtc3VuZGF5JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c3BvbnNvcnNoaXAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy
)​
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Let me ask you a question: even if your job pays well, comes with
great perks, and you enjoy it, do you genuinely find it
fulfilling?

There’s a lot of advice out there about how to find the best
career for you, but it often doesn’t focus on the actual evidence
behind what makes for a truly satisfying career - which is
impact. And that’s where 80,000 Hours (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/6qhehoullnr9geu9/aHR0cHM6Ly84MDAwMGhvdXJzLm9yZy9nZXR0aGVndWlkZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTIwMjUtODBLTUFSLWFsaS1hYmRhYWwtc3VuZGF5JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c3BvbnNvcnNoaXAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy
) comes in.

They’re a non-profit organisation that’s spent over a decade
researching how you can use your career to help solve the world’s
most pressing problems and make a positive difference.

One of the big ones is the rapid growth of AI. Nobody really
knows how powerful AI might become, and finding ways to make AI
safer and better aligned with our values is still a highly
neglected field. Even if you don’t have a technical background,
this could be an area where your skills and knowledge make a
surprisingly big impact.

They’ve got in-depth career guides (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/6qhehoullnr9geu9/aHR0cHM6Ly84MDAwMGhvdXJzLm9yZy9nZXR0aGVndWlkZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTIwMjUtODBLTUFSLWFsaS1hYmRhYWwtc3VuZGF5JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c3BvbnNvcnNoaXAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy
), job hunting tips, 1-1 advising calls, a brilliant podcast, and
a whole bunch of other great resources to help you figure out how
to do the most good with your career.

So whether you’re just starting out, or you’re halfway through
your career and wondering if there’s something more meaningful
you could be doing, I’d highly recommend checking them out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/6qhehoullnr9geu9/aHR0cHM6Ly84MDAwMGhvdXJzLm9yZy9nZXR0aGVndWlkZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTIwMjUtODBLTUFSLWFsaS1hYmRhYWwtc3VuZGF5JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c3BvbnNvcnNoaXAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy
).

Thanks to 80,000 Hours (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/6qhehoullnr9geu9/aHR0cHM6Ly84MDAwMGhvdXJzLm9yZy9nZXR0aGVndWlkZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTIwMjUtODBLTUFSLWFsaS1hYmRhYWwtc3VuZGF5JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c3BvbnNvcnNoaXAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy
) for sponsoring this issue of LifeNotes

P.S. Do you mind taking 50 seconds to
answer a few questions (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/kkhmh2unn6wxqqck/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItc2lnbi11cC10aGFuay15b3UvP3N1cnZleQ==
) so that I can send the most helpful content possible? Thanks in
advance 🙂

If you're enjoying this newsletter, you might also want to
check out my two other newsletters:

1️⃣ ProductiveNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2qxpe9s5ikrp8399u3hoxqzn/vqh2wzv5bmuooe0w79hw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItc2lnbi11cC10aGFuay15b3UvP3Byb2Rub3Rlcw==

https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/qvhmxm2mt8ud62em53sg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1wdXJwb3NlXzI4JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) that’s starting in a few days (you can still sign up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/g3h737pkfwumzog852u3/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1wdXJwb3NlXzI4JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) if you’re interested), I’ve been doing quite a bit of thinking
about something that I know loads of us struggle with - this
whole question of “what’s my purpose?”

Over the last 200 years or so, no one really cared too much about
this stuff. But in the last 20 years, suddenly everyone’s
obsessed with trying to find their big “purpose” in life and back
when I read Anne-Laure’s book, Tiny Experiments (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/48hvh7um2qwddzfq/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3RpbnlleHBlcmltZW50cw==
), there’s this graph that basically shows just how dramatic this
shift’s been:

​
One of the key arguments Anne makes in the book is that this idea
of “finding your purpose” came about as a way to reject
traditional career path thinking. We thought it would give us
more freedom and control over our lives because we’re doing all
this soul-searching and asking ourselves these big existential
questions and stuff, but in reality, setting yourself the goal of
“finding my one true purpose” can be just as restrictive as
locking yourself into the same career for like 50 years or
something.

Back when I spoke to Anne, I found myself really resonating with
this idea because in my own life, there’s this constant
underlying pressure to try and identify the one thing that I’m
supposedly meant to do for the rest of my life.

Don’t get me wrong, I’m a big fan of books like The ONE Thing (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/wnh2h6uqovm225fl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzLzJ1YkJwMWw=
) by Gary Keller and Essentialism (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/reh8h9um5vkll3c6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzLzdSMVZCcw==
) by Greg McKeown, where their message is basically that if you
can find that one true thing, then that’s what will get you out
of bed in the morning and help you feel motivated when motivation
inevitably dips. And there’s definitely truth to that.

But the problem is that we’ve essentially turned “purpose” into a
single destination - a fixed endpoint that we need to reach,
after which everything will just magically make sense. And this
is a classic example of what psychologists call the “arrival
fallacy,” which is the whole idea that once we arrive at a
particular destination, then we’ll be happy.

So in this case, we say to ourselves stuff like “once I’ve found
my purpose, then I’ll be happy” and “once I’ve found my purpose,
then I’ll be doing the right thing.”

But one of the most liberating ideas that I got from the
conversation and from the book was that purpose isn’t something
you find once, like some treasure you dig up and then never have
to think about again. Instead, purpose is something we’re
continuously discovering and rediscovering as we go through life.
It evolves and changes and that’s completely normal.

So if you’ve ever found yourself thinking “what’s my passion?”
and struggled to find an answer, then hopefully this helps you
realise that maybe you’re not the problem. Maybe the real issue
lies in the definition of purpose that we’ve somehow convinced
ourselves to believe - this idea that it has to be this singular,
unchanging, unifying thing that gives everything in your life
meaning.

What if instead of asking “what is my life’s purpose?” we tried
asking: “what gives my life meaning right now, in this season?”

I really like this idea of seasonality, and right now, what gives
my life meaning on the work front is continuing to make YouTube
videos that I think are genuinely helpful and building helpful,
productivity apps that I actually want to use every day (and that
hopefully millions of people can benefit from too).

Anyway, I hope you’ve found this useful - finally, just a quick
reminder that there’s still a couple of days left to sign up to
The $1K Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/3ohphdu3d9x5l8ap/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1wdXJwb3NlXzI4JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) which starts on Friday (August 1st). If you missed my previous
emails, this is a 6-week programme running throughout the summer
to help you take your first steps on your path to financial
freedom. You can get more info here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48e9p9blh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/3ohphdu3d9x5l8ap/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1wdXJwb3NlXzI4JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) - enrolment closes on Thursday evening.

Let me know if reframing “life purpose” → “meaning right now”
helps in dealing with those questions when they arise.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

The Morning

Hello from The New York Times.

Every day, you will be receiving an email from us — called “The Morning” — that
will help you make sense of the day’s biggest news. The email is meant to
provide you with clarity, context and, ideally, some delight.

The Morning gives you a peek inside The Times — at the more than 2,000 Times
journalists stationed in 159 countries, including doctors, lawyers,
cartographers, former Marines and other experts.

We hope this newsletter becomes a part of your morning. See you in your inbox
soon.

— Adam Kushner, editor

column7: 🌞 The 2-for-1 Hour Rule
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you had a good weekend.

Before we get into today’s email, just a quick reminder that I’ll
be hosting our quarterly reset workshop this Saturday (20th
September), and you can sign up here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/9qhmzw0gududpg3e86sz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
). We’ll be focussing on reviewing the last quarter but more
importantly setting ourselves up for success in the final 100
days of 2025 - it’d be great to see you there 🙌

Also - just a note to say thank you to all those people who've
downloaded and tried our latest app, Momentum (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/reh8h9um0qvop7s6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2Rub3Rlcy8xNQ==
), over the past week. It’s really exciting to see so many people
sharing their progress already. If you’ve not downloaded it yet,
you can do so here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/reh8h9um0qvop7s6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2Rub3Rlcy8xNQ==
). (And for all the Android users, we're launching the Android
version in the next couple of weeks - I’ll keep you posted).

Anyway, on with today’s email.

A few weeks ago, we talked about how to structure your day around
ultradian rhythms (if you missed that email, you can check it out
here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/08hwhgu2dmwp4wbp/aHR0cHM6Ly9ja2FyY2hpdmUuY29tL2IvNzV1N2g4aDZvN3Jyemk2cmdnN3JsYXdsODU2NjZ0bmg1bTBuMw==
)), and today I wanted to double-click on this idea of energy
management to optimise our productivity.

Back when I worked as a full-time doctor, it might sound
surprising, but I would actively volunteer to work later in the
day.

My favourite shift was 4pm until midnight, and I’d try my
absolute best to swap with colleagues who had partners and
families and stuff because they preferred to be at home instead
of working late into the night. But I loved it.

Why? Because starting work at 4pm meant I pretty much had the
whole day to make progress on my YouTube videos and growing the
business. I’d then drive to work at 3pm after having a nice
leisurely lunch, work my shift, drive home for an hour, be in bed
by 1am, and sleep until about 10am to repeat the whole cycle
again.

What I noticed was that I always had way more energy before work
than after, and that’s exactly how I harnessed what I call the
2-for-1 Hour Rule, which I learned from one of my professors at
medical school:

“An hour before 9 is worth two after 5.”

In other words, if you spend an hour on something that matters to
you before the demands of the day kick in, it’s worth double the
output you’d get if you left it until you were drained in the
evening.

But this isn’t just a doctor problem. I hear the same story from
so many of our LifeOS (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/8ghqh3uolgp78xil/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNlcHQxNSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlscyZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) and PTYA (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/vqh3hmuopn3q6kfw/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTE1c2VwdCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
) students: they want to build a lifestyle business, launch a
YouTube channel, or write a book, but by the time they get home,
they just don’t have the energy. All they want to do is crash on
the sofa and watch Netflix or scroll on TikTok with their brain
switched off.

Yes, there are lots of ways to make your work more energising and
enjoyable, which I talk about in Feel-Good Productivity, but even
then, admittedly, it’s really hard to finish a long day of work
and not feel frazzled.

That’s why the 2-for-1 Hour Rule is so powerful.

It’s not about joining the 4am club (which I’m definitely not a
part of 😅) or squeezing every hour out of the day - it’s about
recognising when you’re most energised and building your day
around those times, instead of relying on your most drained hours
to do your most important work.

So for me, that meant using my mornings before going into the
hospital to get stuff done. I’d often plan YouTube videos and
tinker away at scripts during my lunch breaks as well if I wasn’t
hanging out and socialising with my colleagues, because it was
way more effective than waiting until I got home after work when
I knew (as with most people), I just wanted to relax and switch
off.

Perhaps it’s not the morning for you but once you’ve figured out
your natural peaks and dips of energy, you can design an ideal
day that works with the way you feel, not against it.

This is what I call “Productive Days” within LifeOS (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/8ghqh3uolgp78xil/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNlcHQxNSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlscyZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
), and when you start stacking these together, you end up with
your ideal week - where your time and energy are split
harmoniously across all domains of work and life.

If you give this a try this week, hit reply and let me know how
it goes - I’d love to hear when you feel most energised during
your day.

And remember, if you want to join me this Saturday for our final
reset workshop of the year, you can sign up here (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/qvh38o0wi8udr82l34sg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
) - would love to see you there.

Have a great week 🙌

Ali xx

Update Your Email Preferences (
https://unsubscribe.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290
) | Unsubscribe from ProductiveNotes (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hlmkm6zhrh8dmk999imhon290/vqh22r4vfmuopn3q6ntw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NvcnJ5LXRvLXNlZS15b3UtZ28_cHJvZHVjdGl2aXZ0eWxhYg==
) |

column7: [GoodBarber] Tip 1/9: Off to a good start with the creation of your app!
column9:
Hello ,

Now it's time for you get acquainted with your back office. For a smooth start to creating your app, we suggest you start exploring the "Get Started" (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/dashboard/) guide on your Dashboard. 
The content of this guide is a good starting point to build your project. You can work on each item of the list independently.  

So, don’t waste time and follow the guide:

DISCOVER (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/dashboard/)

We hope this will be useful!
If you looking for more tips, go ahead and download our eBook (https://get.goodbarber.com/the-ultimate-goodbarber-guide/).

If you need help, feel free to contact our support team (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/support/).

Sincerely,
The GoodBarber support team
        
            Unsubscribe from this list (https://goodbarber.com/unsubscribe/61a9a24cefc3e6b32be2675cd139587b7d4aa3e6)

column7: A reminder about time management...
column9:
Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - if you haven’t already, you might
want to check out CreatorNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/n2hohquv6ez2x5f0/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NyZWF0b3Itbm90ZXMvP2xtLWdh
), my weekly email newsletter for creators where I talk about all
things YouTube and building a business around making content.
Every week, I share behind-the-scenes stuff from running my own
channel, lessons that my team and I are learning, and a bunch of
bonus content, so if that sounds interesting, you can subscribe
in one-click by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/3oh4z6kdsdu34vex2nbp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi9jcmVhdG9yLW5vdGVzLW9wdC1pbi1jb25maXJtYXRpb24v
).

Anyway, I wanted to tell you about a moment that happened this
morning that I’m highly proud of. I’ve just gotten back to Hong
Kong from LA where I spent a week attending an event hosted by
Taki Moore (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/wnh2h6uqx8emkoul/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQFRha2lNb29yZQ==
), aimed at 7-figure-and-above online coach type people, which I
guess I fall into the category of. Amazing experience including a
hot-air balloon and tonnes of notes taken, I’ll share more at
some point. But I got back yesterday, slept at a reasonable hour,
but then woke up at 5am this morning and couldn’t get back to
sleep.

So naturally, I reached for my phone, and opened up YouTube. And
on my homepage, I came across this video where entrepreneur
Steven Bartlett was being interviewed by entrepreneur Rachel Lim
in Singapore (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/reh8h9umwngk3qb6/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj11ZHZLQjMxMC1fdw==
). Fun fact - Izzy and I had breakfast with Rachel a couple
months ago, lovely lady, super inspiring.

I flicked through the timestamps, listened to some stuff about
the importance of hiring great team members, some stuff the
importance of experimentation in business and life, AND THEN
Steven talked about the way he thinks about time management in
terms of Playing Roulette Chips.

It’s an analogy he wrote about in his first book Happy Sexy
Millionaire (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/08hwhgu2gq3n9dhp/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL0R0UVF2
) - good book, the title’s supposed to be cringe don’t worry, the
whole message is “when I was a kid I thought I wanted to be a
happy sexy millionaire, and then I got there and realised that
other than ‘happy’ those were the wrong things to aim for, sort
of”.

The analogy is as follows: time is our most valuable non
renewable resource. Once we’ve used up an hour, we can never get
it back. So we can think of each hour of our time as a “chip” in
a casino. We get 24 chips everyday, and each hour, we have to
take one of our chips, and play it in a particular spot on the
roulette table.

Each hour that passes in life, it’s like we’ve allocated one of
our chips to a particular activity. 2 hours at the gym = 2 chips.
4 hours on Netflix and 3 on TikTok = 7 chips. You get the idea.
24 chips in a day, 168 chips in a week.

Every hour that passes, we’re making decisions about where we’ve
placed that chip. We can make the decision intentionally, or
unintentionally. And most of us make most of our chip-allocation
decisions unintentionally. So, if we want to improve our lives,
be happier, healthier, more fulfilled, more “successful” - a good
starting point is to be more intentional about where we allocate
those chips, ie: where we spend our time.

You can do this by asking yourself each hour: “What would I like
to actually spend the next hour doing? How would I like to
allocate this upcoming chip?”

That’s not to say that you need to be hyper efficient and always
be working, obviously. Allocating a chip to spending time with
your spouse, or your kid, or your work, or video gaming, or even
scrolling Instagram Reels, is totally fine - as long as it’s
intentional rather than unconscious.

So anyway, by the time I finish watching this YouTube video, it’s
5:30am, and I’m inspired. I think to myself: “Huh okay so I
probably can’t go back to sleep given the jet lag, so how would I
like to allocate this next hour of my life?”

And I decided: “You know what, it would be nice to go for a run”.

And so, I put on my running shorts, whacked on my trainers, put
my headphones in, and headed out of the house to do the earliest
run I’ve literally ever done in my life.

And it was great! I ran for 30 minutes, while listening to some
“guided running meditation” thing, and felt awesome afterwards.

Then I continued the exercise of asking myself a few times
throughout the day: “Huh okay so how do I want to allocate this
next chip?” (Ie: the next hour of time) and each time, the fact
that I paused to ask myself that question helped me make a better
decision about it.

On weekdays, the decision about how to spend each hour is kinda
decided by what’s on the calendar already (using one of the
components of the Trident Method (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/8ghqh3uoqkmw2ofl/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS82bzJ0bTAwQXI4QT9zaT12bzc0OTcwZUlLQlVtNmlO
) that I made a video about a few years ago). But especially in
the mornings before work, on free evenings after work, and
definitely on the weekends, I’d like to be a little more
intentional with how I’m actually using my time, rather than
defaulting to watching random stuff on my phone. The chip thing
helps :)

Have a great week!

Ali xx

P.S. Do you mind taking 50 seconds to
answer a few questions (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/vqh3hmuoe8zmvetw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItc2lnbi11cC10aGFuay15b3UvP3N1cnZleQ==
) so that I can send the most helpful content possible? Thanks in
advance 🙂

If you're enjoying this newsletter, you might also want to
check out my two other newsletters:

1️⃣ ProductiveNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/wnhqo5zec6uqx8emkgsl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItc2lnbi11cC10aGFuay15b3UvP3Byb2Rub3Rlcw==
): Weekly actionable productivity tips to help you do more of
what matters.

2️⃣ CreatorNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2z9qkvhzi4qpepnns7h6x45l/vqh2wzvmimuoe8zmv8sw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItc2lnbi11cC10aGFuay15b3UvP2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
): Weekly tips for aspiring creators to create more consistent
and high-value content.

YouTube (

) | Instagram (

column7: Learn about diversity, equity, and inclusion at the I School
column9:
Hello Candace,

            I hope this email finds you well! Here at the I School, we have just welcomed an incredible new cohort of students who showcase our cultural and academic diversity! In addition, we are preparing for a busy admissions season full of dynamic recruiting events <https://www.ischool.berkeley.edu/programs/mims/events>. We are also excited for the crisp air, changing leaves and the season's new beginnings.

            Last week, Chancellor Rich Lyons shared a video message <https://news.berkeley.edu/2025/08/27/watch-a-message-from-chancellor-lyons-welcoming-uc-berkeley-to-a-new-academic-year/> welcoming the UC Berkeley community back to campus. In it, he reaffirms Berkeley's commitment to seven principles of community <https://chancellor.berkeley.edu/about/principles-community> and shares his vision for how we can protect Berkeley's core values and plan for the future.

            Chancellor Lyons shared: "Berkeley is more than a place; it's a promise...And those principles are what enable us to deliver on that promise. They support an environment where all can thrive and feel a sense of belonging, where the freedom to teach, learn and discover is revered and protected, and where we embrace the central role of diversity and pluralism in the life of our university: the diversity of origins and identities, of beliefs and perspectives, of academic interests and pursuits."

            This year promises to be particularly rich with learning, discovery, and meaningful dialogue on issues impacting our communities, nation, and the world. Berkeley has always been a place where big ideas are born from challenging convention and a robust exchange of diverse perspectives.

            I look forward to continuing to share exciting and complex conversations and issues around DEIBJ work happening at the I School and UC Berkeley. I hope these newsletters will spark thought, share something new, or encourage dialogue about ways to make us better. If you would like to chat further or contribute to this newsletter, please reach out!

            Warmly,
            Roxanne

Roxanne Pifer
            Director of Admissions & Diversity Recruitment
            UC Berkeley School of Information

I School News

Oxford-Berkeley Summer Doctoral Program Brings Diverse Information Studies Scholars to UC Berkeley <https://www.ischool.berkeley.edu/news/2025/oxford-berkeley-summer-doctoral-program-brings-diverse-information-studies-scholars-uc>
            Students from across the world traveled to the UC Berkeley campus to attend the Summer Doctoral Program. The Oxford Internet Institute at the University of Oxford has hosted the Summer Doctoral Programme since 2003, and this year marked the start of a new collaboration between Oxford and Berkeley, which will see participants alternating between the two locations every other year. 

Ph.D. Student Wins Best Paper Award For Earth Observation AI Model <https://www.ischool.berkeley.edu/news/2025/phd-student-wins-best-paper-award-earth-observation-ai-model>
            In a world where signs of global warming are becoming increasingly common, data has become a critical component in the fight against climate change. In recent years, with the help of satellites and other remote sensing platforms, researchers have been able to observe and track minute changes in the Earth's surface, waters, and atmosphere. This course of study, called Earth observation, has been at the forefront of many papers shown at this year's EarthVision Conference.          

Campus Events

UC Berkeley's Graduate Diversity Admissions Fair <https://grad.berkeley.edu/admissions/why-berkeley/graduate-diversity-admissions-fair/>
            Join UC Berkeley's virtual Graduate Diversity Admissions Fair for five days of interactive sessions with over 70 graduate programs. Designed for all prospective students, especially those from diverse backgrounds, the fair offers one-hour sessions, discussion groups, and insider insights on applying, thriving, and advancing in graduate school. Discover Berkeley's culture, resources, research, and career opportunities.
                       


UC Berkeley School of Information <https://www.ischool.berkeley.edu> - 102 South Hall, Berkeley, CA 94720-4600 

            You are receiving this email because you requested information about the School of Information.          







This email was sent to aicoaching2025@gmail.com by Berkeley I School Admissions.
Unsubscribe from University of California, Berkeley. <https://gradapp.berkeley.edu/go?r=optout&mid=2cb1dc97-5121-41dd-9648-bbb9e1dae945>

column7: Let's go over the transcript request process
column9:
https://click.sfmc2.edx.org/?qs=e88c5dec58b0c574ba23b87ccd5143ec8527748c1cae285b19c8b16b0892a3defd523e19b4300de70673ed9ba9a25611bbc275367cca9a2e8707829ddc8dbf81 



A guide to requesting your transcripts
Let's get your application ready

Work on your application >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/>
 
We recommend starting the transcript request process as early as possible because it may take some extra time. To apply to the Master of Information and Data Science, you will need to submit transcripts from all academic institutions you've attended. 

 We accept unofficial transcripts to render an admissions decision, but we will need to receive official transcripts before you can register for classes. 

 You may upload copies of your transcripts to your online application for unofficial review. To be considered official, transcripts must be sent to us directly by your previous institution(s).

column7: Your application checklist ✔
column9:
https://click.sfmc2.edx.org/?qs=2c053350dc6feb1e6fde3f8a25fe582c6ec93547cd1d2fab644ba624bf1969c28ce5e283cb86f1188ff86b0e48673af4b9bf88be3c6cba4b7cc108440b7f0ce2 



 To help you throughout the application process, we've compiled a checklist of application requirements for your reference.

Note: You'll always find the most up-to-date information in your online application https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/. That's where you can see your progress, the application items you've already submitted, and the upcoming start date for the Master of Information and Data Science.
 
Application requirement checklist

Here's everything you'll need to do to complete your application:


	- Fill out the online application:  The online application captures information about your personal, professional, and academic background.
	- Request transcripts:  You’ll have to include transcripts from all schools you’ve attended. You may upload unofficial transcripts for the initial review of your application.
	- Submit contact info for recommender(s):  At least 2 recommenders are required.
	- Attach your résumé:  Make sure it’s up to date.
	- Upload your Statement of Purpose:  This is your opportunity to show the admissions committee why you’re a good fit for the program.
	- Pay the application fee:  The fee is $135 for domestic applications and $155 for international applicants. Waivers may be available.

We will be sending you more information about each of these application requirements soon. In the meantime, log in to the application <https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/> to see your progress so far.

We're here to support you. Ready to take the next step? The Master of Information and Data Science is designed for working professionals looking for a world-renowned education without putting their personal or professional commitments on hold. You’ll be supported every step of the way — from application to graduation.

An Enrollment Specialist is available to answer any questions you may have. You can reach out at (510) 924-3473 or admissions@datascience.berkeley.edu, or schedule some time on their calendar <https://app.grooveapp.com/meetings/0054X00000DbgbK>.
 
Work on your application >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/>

column7: [PythonAnywhere] Schedule a task to run automatically
column9:
Tick tock tick tock tick tock.  It's the passage of time -- so familiar and yet, so mysterious; there's no good explanation for it in Physics! Will we ever truly understand it? Who knows...

But one thing's for sure, and that's the fact that you can HARNESS THE POWER OF TIME using PythonAnywhere Scheduled Tasks. Something we see you haven't had *time* to do yet, ho ho.[1]

So head on over to the Tasks tab where you'll be able to set any Python script (or, indeed, any other kind of script) to run on a regular basis

https://www.pythonanywhere.com/user/jabjabcarnival/tasks_tab/


With your free account, you can set tasks to run once a day.


Here's a few ideas to get you started:

* Send yourself an email once a day reminding you to floss your teeth

* Write a script to scrape daily prices 3D-printed plastic models of classic designs for fire hydrants.  Finally you'll be able to make those crucial buying decisions at the best time!

* Write a twitter bot that posts the time of day once a day, and helpfully @-mentions random people informing them of what time it is

* Download all the books on project gutenberg that were written on that day in history, and compute a hash of their text contents, just because!

The possibilities are endless.

[1] The original author of this email was already on their final
warning for bad puns, and has now been summarily dismissed.


Happy Scheduling!


Piotr + the PythonAnywhere team.


Piotr Kaznowski
Developer

including pointing you towards some cool features that are a bit hidden.

you can do so here:
