column7: Why You Should Set Your Vision Before 2026
column9:
Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - we’ve recently made some updates
and changes to Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/6qhehoullozpq7c9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2Rub3Rlc18xMw==
), the app that we launched last month, so if you’ve not tried it
yet, you can download it and get a 3-day free trial here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/6qhehoullozpq7c9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2Rub3Rlc18xMw==
). (We’re aiming to launch the Android version within the next
couple of weeks - please bear with us, it is coming!)

Hope you had a great weekend 😊

We’re now back into the swing of a normal working routine after a
couple of disrupted weeks with the team offsite followed by a
week of food poisoning which wasn't great but did give me more
time to consume more Harry Potter fan fiction 😅

Anyway, I wanted to use today’s email to reflect on the vision
board I made back in January when my wife Izzy hosted a vision
boarding workshop as part of our annual planning event. And yes,
we’ll be running another one of these in 2026 - I’ll announce it
in these emails when we’ve got dates sorted 👀

A vision board is essentially this powerful pictorial
representation of your goals, dreams, and aspirations, and this
is what mine looked like at the start of the year:

​
Izzy and I had our first kid. We literally just moved into our
new team office here in Hong Kong the other week. We’ve launched
another app called Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/6qhehoullozpq7c9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2Rub3Rlc18xMw==
). And while I’m not doing martial arts anymore, I’ve gotten
really into tennis instead, which I personally find way more fun
and energising.

Now I’m not saying I’ve ticked everything off - obviously I
haven’t. But looking back at this vision board I threw together
in 15 minutes at the start of the year, I’m genuinely surprised
by how much has shifted in the right direction.

I always remind my LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/58hvh8ugg7q5ekf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXZpc2lvbl8xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
) students that it’s really difficult to make any kind of
meaningful change in your life if you don’t have a compelling
vision for where you want to go.

You don’t need to know exactly where you want to end up - life
has a habit of punching us in the face sometimes anyway 😅 But you
do need some sort of direction to aim towards, because if your
ideal vision for the future doesn’t actually feel better or more
exciting than where you are right now, then there’s no motivation
to make changes happen.

And that’s exactly what a vision board does - it gives you that
direction.

By looking at your vision board daily, you’re also signalling to
a part of your brain called the Reticular Activating System (RAS)
that these goals are important to you.

Your RAS acts like a filter for all the sensory information
you’re constantly bombarded with - everything from what you see
and hear to random thoughts - and it categorises about 99% of it
as “not important,” letting it pass by unnoticed.

But when you regularly look at your vision board, you’re flagging
those images and goals as important, which means your RAS
suddenly starts noticing opportunities related to them that you
might have missed before.

Just to be clear: a vision board isn’t a magical manifestation
tool. And by sticking a bunch of pictures on a board, I’m not
saying the universe will deliver your dream on a silver platter.

Instead, a vision board is a focus tool.

I still had to actually search for office spaces (or delegate
this to Becky on the team 😅), build the apps, and show up to
tennis practice… but the vision board just helped me clarify my
goals and keep them front of mind.

This whole concept of visualising your life a few years from now
is part of The Future Sketch module in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/58hvh8ugg7q5ekf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXZpc2lvbl8xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
), where we explore different methods for creating a compelling
vision that’s actually aligned with your values - check it out
here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/58hvh8ugg7q5ekf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXZpc2lvbl8xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
) if you’re interested.

But even if you don't join LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l/58hvh8ugg7q5ekf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXZpc2lvbl8xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
), I’d genuinely encourage you to spend 15 minutes this week
throwing together a quick vision board.

It doesn’t need to be fancy or perfect. Just grab a few images
that make you think “yeah, that would be cool” and stick them
somewhere you’ll see regularly (whether that’s digitally or
physically).

Let me know how you get on - hit reply and feel free to share it
with me.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

Update Your Email Preferences (
https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6g8klxuvhq4dm8rrcohqe49l
) | Unsubscribe from ProductiveNotes (

) |

column7: Do your case studies showcase your best work? Find out in lesson 3 of “Build a Standout UX/UI Portfolio: Land Your Dream Job”
column9:
Hi Candace, 

How can you write a compelling case study? In lesson 3, we’ll explore how to create successful case studies thatn effectively demonstrate your skills and experience.  

Get started right now at: 

https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/build-a-standout-ux-ui-portfolio-land-your-dream-job 

Here's what's coming up: 

- Effective hooks for case studies. 

- The research section. 

- Showcase your design process with sketches and wireframes. 

- Prototypes. 

 

You’ll also apply all the knowledge you’ve gathered and continue with the portfolio project you began in the previous lesson.  

 

We’ll release one lesson per week based on the schedule below: 

--- Course schedule ---
Available now: Welcome and Introduction
Available now: Attract Success: Your Portfolio is the Key to Design Your Dream Career
Available now: Hook Hiring Managers' Attention with Your Design Portfolio
Available now: How to Make Your Case Studies Stand Out and Tell Your Story
Aug 13th, 2025: Land Your Dream Job with a Standout Portfolio
Aug 20th, 2025: Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up 

 

Happy learning! 

 

PS: You’ll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

Morgane Peng
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column7: 🎲 How To Make Better Decisions
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you had a great weekend 🙌

I’m writing this from Bali where we’ve just concluded our
bi-annual team offsite. The purpose of these weeks is to align on
our plans for the upcoming quarter but there’s also an intangible
ROI of just getting the team together that never fails to
surprise me. If you’ve read my book, you’ll know that I place
quite a bit of importance on people when it comes to productivity
- not just from an accountability perspective but also in terms
of the energy that you get from working together and that was
proven again this week (up until the final day when I got food
poisoning which wasn’t the most energising of experiences 😅).

Anyway, enough about our offsite and on to today’s email where I
wanted to build upon something that I talked about in one of my
recent YouTube videos and that’s something called the Think Day
Method.

This is a technique I came across in Sahil Bloom’s book, The 5
Types of Wealth (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436/8ghqh3uoox3wnntl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2tqaUlx
) and the idea is that you set aside at least 4 hours out of your
normal routine to think, journal, and read, and in doing so, you
can drastically change the trajectory of your life.

One of the things to keep in mind here is that changing your life
ultimately comes down to the decisions you make, meaning, the
quality of your decisions dictates the quality of your life.

If you make a decision that causes you to take actions that move
you in a positive direction, then your life changes for the
better, and if you take actions that move you in a negative
direction, your life changes for the worse.

But decision-making isn’t always easy, and something I’ve been
thinking about a lot lately is this phenomenon called the paradox
of choice.

The psychologist, Barry Schwartz, ran this now-famous experiment
at a food market where he set up a table offering jam samples to
shoppers - on some days, he displayed 6 different varieties of
jam and on other days, he displayed 24.

Now, you’d think more options would be better since more choice
means more chance of finding exactly what you want.

But the results were exactly the opposite.

When there were only 6 jams on display, people shopping were far
more likely to actually buy something, whereas when there were 24
options, people felt overwhelmed, struggled to make a decision,
and often walked away without buying anything at all.

This is the paradox of choice in action - the more options we
have, the harder it becomes to make a decision and the less
satisfied we tend to be with the outcome.

And this doesn’t just apply to jam (though that would be annoying
enough). It impacts everything from simple decisions like
choosing your next holiday destination, to more complicated ones
like picking a career path or a life partner.

I’ve even been experiencing this myself recently when developing
our new product the Lifestyle Business Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436/vqh3hmuood4mr7cw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVzdHlsZS1idXNpbmVzcy1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj10aGlua2RheV82JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kbm90ZXM=
) and trying to decide the optimal length of the programme to
maximise results for people.

The irony is that we think having unlimited options gives us more
freedom and makes us happier, but it often just leads to
overwhelm, decision paralysis, and regret. We’re constantly
wondering if we made the “right” choice or if there was something
better we missed.

So what can you do about it?

Well, first you want to intentionally limit your choices. I like
to do this through journaling. I know this might sound a bit
obvious and gets talked about a lot in the productivity space but
it really does work and helps me get super clear on my values and
priorities, and, by eliminating options that don’t align with
what matters most to me, any subsequent decisions become way
easier.

Second, stop expecting every decision to be perfect. Every choice
involves giving up alternatives, so you want to look for a “good
enough” option rather than searching endlessly for the
objectively “best” choice, and then commit to that decision once
you’ve made it. Of course, you should take learnings from every
decision that you make but waiting for the perfect amount of
information to make the perfect decision will often leave you in
this state of overwhelm and decision paralysis.

I know this is a lot easier said than done, but even just being
aware of the paradox of choice puts you ahead of most people who
are unconsciously paralysed by it.

And if you want to watch the full video, you can find it on my
channel here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436/l2heh6ullz4q7msg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1nTzBidlRfc21kTQ==
) and you can also download my Think Day Guide here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436/m2h7h6u33792zdal/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoaW5rLWRheS1ndWlkZT91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249dGhpbmtkYXlfNiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
) which gives you a load of prompts, templates and exercises I
use myself whenever I'm doing one of these Think Days.

Have a great week ahead and let me know how you get on with your
own Think Days and whether you find the prompts in the Think Day
Guide (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436/e0hph0u772emodh7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoaW5rLWRheS1ndWlkZQ==
) helpful 🙌

Talk soon,

Ali xx

Update Your Email Preferences (
https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh3w9vv2a2hdevlm66s7hmo436

column7: Release Day: Design View is here — style your site in seconds
column9:
Happy July Release Day! ( https://www.relume.io/whats-new/july-2025-release?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )

Hey Candace,

Happy July Release Day! 🎉

If you’ve been watching our Community Roadmap ( https://www.relume.io/roadmap?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ), you might’ve spotted a mysterious “secret project” brewing. Today, the curtain lifts.

Meet Design View — a new way to style your Relume wireframes with just a few clicks. Alongside Design View, we’re also shipping: Smarter Style Guide generation and a fresh batch of new components.

Let’s break it all down.

*
Design View (Beta) - Today, we’re unveiling Design View — a lightning-fast styling tool built directly into Relume. Instantly apply your Style Guide (colors, typography, and UI elements) across your entire site in just a few clicks. Preview your fully styled site visually before exporting to Figma or Webflow. Try Design View now ( https://www.relume.io/dashboard?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )
* Smarter Style Guide generation - We’ve replaced random shuffling with a smarter system powered by LLMs. Now, your colors, typography, and UI styles are chosen based on the company you're designing for — so your Style Guide starts on-brand and on-aesthetic from the jump.
*
New Components - We've added a fresh batch of 80 Feature Sections and 8 CTA Sections that all have expanded, full-bleed images. These work seamlessly across both Wireframe view and Design view — so you can wireframe, style, and export without skipping a beat. Browse new components ( https://www.relume.io/components?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )
*
Figma Kit Update v3.3 - We have added the 88 new components to our Relume Figma Kit, which is available in both desktop and mobile variants. To receive the latest update, visit the Figma Library ( https://www.relume.io/figma-library?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ) in your dashboard.
 Community Roadmap ( https://www.relume.io/roadmap?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )We've moved the top-voted items into in-progress which means you can expect to see these drop in upcoming release days.

*
Save Page Templates
* Browser Preview
* More Components
 Read the full What’s New ( https://www.relume.io/whats-new/july-2025-release?layout_id=&utm_campaign=Release+Day+-+July&utm_content=July+Release+Day&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )Big thanks to our amazing community — your feedback, ideas, and support for one another inspire us to keep building, improving, and delivering more every month.

Stay productive Lumers! 🫡⚡

column7: How To Make Money On YouTube
column9:
Hey Candace,

Quick thing before we start - we’ve just finalised the date for
my next quarterly alignment workshop, which will be happening on
Saturday 20th September. This is a great opportunity for you to
reflect on the last couple of months but, more importantly, set
yourself up for success in the final 100 days of 2025. If you’re
interested in joining, you can register with just one click here.
(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hl34v2pbrh8dmk999imhon290/m2h2oeomh6u3o68d90tl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW9uZSUyMGNsaWNrJTIwb3B0JTIwaW4mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
)​

Anyway, I’ve recently been looking back through all the footage
from our events in London (I usually listen to this on 2x speed
during my gym sessions), and one of them was a mastermind for
entrepreneurs already making six figures.

Now, I know most of you reading this won’t be in that exact
position 😅 But a lot of you are thinking about starting a YouTube
channel, either to build an audience or to grow your business.

And this is where I think it’s super important to understand the
difference between two very different approaches to YouTube that
I talk about in PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hl34v2pbrh8dmk999imhon290/owhkhwuw4mr2n7cq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5XzMmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
): the Creator First approach vs the Business First approach.

The Creator First approach is where your focus is on building an
audience and not necessarily making any money from YouTube at
first. But if your aim is to grow a business, prioritising views
and subscribers and going viral can actually hold you back.

Why? Because a successful business is built around a core offer
that speaks to a very specific target audience.

So with the Business First approach, your goal is to create
videos that speak to a very specific type of person with a very
specific problem, so they land on your channel and immediately
think “wow, this is exactly for me.”

And there’s one channel I’ve been obsessed with lately that’s a
perfect example. A video by a guy called Taki Moore (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hl34v2pbrh8dmk999imhon290/z2hgh7ueo23q7dhz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQFRha2lNb29yZQ==
) popped up for me recently, and I ended up binge-watching a
bunch of his videos and even signing up for his $60k/year
mastermind.

But the thing is, he only has just over 10k subscribers and his
videos only get about 1k views. So his channel is ‘tiny’ in the
grand scheme of things, but because his content is so specific -
targeting coaches already making six figures who want to scale
and reach that next level - his business is hugely profitable.

And I’ve seen this pattern play out over and over again,
especially in recent months where even larger creators are
choosing to start over with smaller business-first channels to
address a more targeted audience. Why? Because they’ve recognised
that small channels with content that speaks to one specific
audience avatar and is deeply aligned with their offer can be
incredibly profitable - even from day one.

I found myself giving this advice to a bunch of the entrepreneurs
who came to this mastermind event that we hosted in London, as
well as a lot of people who’ve been taking our $1K Challenge and
using YouTube as a way to sell their products and services.

So hopefully that was useful if you’re thinking about taking the
Business First approach to YouTube and worrying that you’re going
to need millions of views or hundreds of thousands of subscribers
before you can ‘make money’. If you’re able to speak to the right
person, in the right way, YouTube can be an incredibly profitable
marketing channel, even with a small audience.

If you’re taking this approach, I’d love to know what you’re
currently struggling with - hit reply and let me know.

Talk soon,

Ali xx

P.S - just a reminder, you can sign up for the quarterly workshop
just by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/gku7mr0d8xb5hl34v2pbrh8dmk999imhon290/m2h2oeomh6u3o68d90tl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW9uZSUyMGNsaWNrJTIwb3B0JTIwaW4mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
). Look forward to seeing you there 🙌

).

column7: Why I Wrote “Junior YouTuber” in my Instagram Bio
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’re having a great week so far. I'm back in London for a
couple of weeks so currently overcoming a bit of jet lag whilst
working out a temporary filming set-up (one of the reasons I just
love having everything permanently set-up at home is that there's
no friction to filming 😅).

Anyway, I actually wanted to use this email today to talk about
something that came up during our most recent workshop that we
hosted in Hong Kong and it all relates to imposter syndrome.

Now, I know we’ve spoken a bit about imposter syndrome in these
emails before, but the reason I return to it so often is that
it’s one of the top things holding a lot of people back when it
comes to starting a YouTube channel or even just putting
themselves out there in any capacity. In fact, it’s been coming
up a lot with students within our $1k Challenge too so I thought
it was worth revisiting.

So I guess the first thing to say is that there’s no way to
eliminate imposter syndrome completely. It exists at every single
level of every single thing you do, and the only way to not feel
imposter syndrome is to stay safely within the confines of you
comfort zone. As soon as you venture beyond this, doing anything
that’s even vaguely “out there”, you experience some sense of
imposter syndrome because you feel like you don’t belong there.

I think it’s easy for a lot of people to assume that I no longer
feel any of these sorts of emotions and mental blocks. With 6
million subs on YouTube, a small team and a successful business,
surely I don’t feel these things? But to keep things super real
and transparent with you all, I’d say for about 90% of the
YouTube videos that I’ve ever made in my life - and I’ve made
over 1,000 - I’ve felt some level of imposter syndrome. (I even
talked about it a bit in one of my recent videos here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp0707kixh6pmxm77i5h6gnw9/3ohphdu3d0oxn9ap/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS94bTJDZ09LU0UtVT9zaT1MVlQ0MXAtTHdYRHE2OU1z
)).

Even away from YouTube, according to my publishers, I’m a
“productivity expert” but writing my book was a pretty painful
process because I put a lot of pressure on myself for it to be a
really good, detailed, thorough work of non-fiction and I felt
like I needed to live up to this reputation of being a Cambridge
graduate, doctor and productivity expert with this huge online
audience. It's partly why it took a few years from idea to
publication - that sense of imposter syndrome was hovering about
most of the time.

Having said that, there are all sorts of ways to help manage
imposter syndrome, and one thing I’ve found helpful is super
simple but it’s really effective. Essentially it boils down to
giving yourself permission to be a beginner.

Back when I first started making YouTube videos, I updated my
Instagram bio to say “Junior YouTuber.” And there was something
about doing this that gave me permission to make YouTube videos
because I was like, “I’m not a real YouTuber. I’m just a Junior
YouTuber - a YouTuber in training,” sort of like a junior doctor.

But you don’t need Instagram or a big following to use this
approach - you could update your LinkedIn headline, your email
signature, or just how you introduce yourself to people or even
how you think about your identity yourself.

Instead of needing to be “a content creator,” you could be
“someone who’s learning to create content”. I know people who
literally just tell themselves “I’m a part-time entrepreneur”
when they’re building something on the side, and there’s
something about that identity that gives you permission to learn
and make mistakes while you figure out how to actually do the
thing.

And whilst keeping the identity piece to yourself can work, the
most effective way is to publicly commit to the “trainee” version
of whatever you want to become, which then takes the pressure off
being perfect and gives you permission to be in learning mode.
Whether that's through your social media bios or telling other
people, that public commitment adds an element of accountability
too which acts as a bit of a catalyst in overcoming those
feelings.

I think the school system sometimes drives a lot of us into
feeling imposter syndrome because we’re taught that you need to
have a certificate or qualification to do anything. But my whole
thing is that you don’t have to be a guru, you can just be a
guide - in fact, I’d recommend seeing yourself as a guide because
it just makes everything easier.

You don’t have to know everything - you just have to be one step
ahead of someone else on their journey. And once you actually do
the thing, you eventually realise that imposter syndrome is just
a feeling. And like with all feelings - they’re just feelings.
Feelings aren’t facts, feelings don’t have to dictate your
actions, and you can feel the thing and do it anyway - this is
often called courage.

So if you’ve ever felt imposter syndrome when it comes to sharing
stuff on the internet, my best piece of advice is to be like
“hey, I don’t have all the answers, but I’m just trying to share
something I think might be helpful to at least one other person,”
and that’s often the best way to go.

The other thing to remember is to recognise that you’re not alone
in having these feelings. As I said, I still get waves of
imposter syndrome when I’m sitting down to film or even getting
up to do these in-person talks that sparked this whole email 😅 -
it's not something that you're experiencing on your own.

One of the other things that I've not mentioned that can
specifically help manage this feeling is community. We’ve seen
over the past four years that one of the key benefits that people
get from joining PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp0707kixh6pmxm77i5h6gnw9/n2hohquvom82kks0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWltcG9zdGVyXzYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) is the access to the community and the thousands of other
students who are all creators and therefore understand the
struggles around imposter syndrome that arise at every stage of
the YouTube journey. If you think that’d be helpful, you can sign
up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp0707kixh6pmxm77i5h6gnw9/n2hohquvom82kks0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWltcG9zdGVyXzYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

Anyway, I hope this email has provided some tools for you to help
manage imposter syndrome as those feelings arise on your own
YouTube journey.

Have a great rest of the week and don’t let imposter syndrome
hold you back 💪

We’ll speak again next Wednesday :)

Ali xx

P.S - if you are a complete beginner, you’ve never made a video
before, and imposter syndrome is holding you back, then you might
want to check out the 7 Video Challenge instead. It’s
specifically designed to help you take those first steps into
content creation and overcome those feelings that are leading to
inaction - more info here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp0707kixh6pmxm77i5h6gnw9/48hvh7um2v5wn2sq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249aW1wb3N0ZXJfNiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

🚀 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp0707kixh6pmxm77i5h6gnw9/wnh2h6uqon5m3rfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
).

Kay Chun reimagines classic Italian sausage and peppers as a fast pasta dinner.
The flavors here are spot-on, but it’s the textures that make it pure pleasure
to eat: the softened, slippery peppers; the nubby browned sausage; the chewy
rigatoni; the tender-crisp broccoli bites.

After last month's Masterclass, I got a ton of DMs and emails asking if we would ever run it again.

So, I have some exciting news!

Next Thursday, August 21st at 9 AM PST, I'll be hosting a new & improved Prompt Your Way To Profit Masterclass.

So if you didn't make it last time or you want a refresher, I'd love to have you!

Here's what I'll cover:

Prompt Your Way To Profit: Discover The 4 Prompts Freelance Writers Are Using *Right Now* To Make $100,000+ Per Year

In this Masterclass, I'll cover the 4 pillars of becoming an AI ghostwriter:

• Pillar #1: Positioning - Why you shouldn’t call yourself a “freelance writer” anymore, and how to position yourself as a Premium Ghostwriter instead.

• Pillar #2: Packaging - How to stop charging per word, or per hour, and instead charge a premium by selling a repeatable, productized service.

• Pillar #3: Outreach - How to find warm & cold clients, identify problems you can help them solve, and reach out to them (without being sales-y).

• Pillar #4: Fulfillment - How to use AI to do 80% of the work. Whether you’re ghostwriting short-form social content, weekly newsletters, or social media management and engagement.

And we will show you our exact AI prompts to help you implement all of this 10x faster.

column7: ⭐ What’s Your Dream?
column9:
Hey Candace,

Earlier this year, Simon Squibb flew out to meet me here in Hong
Kong. If you don’t recognise the name, you might’ve seen Simon’s
content pop up in your social media feeds over the past couple of
years. He’s been asking thousands of people one simple question -
“what’s your dream?” - and he’s even written a best-selling book
with the same title.

Anyway, when he came to meet me here in Hong Kong, we hung out in
real life, filmed a bunch of content together, and he asked me
that same question.

So I thought it would be fun to share a snippet of our
conversation with you today because there’s an important lesson
here when it comes to productivity… but first here’s how that
part of our conversation went:

Simon: “What’s your dream?”

Me: “I’d have to think about that. What’s my dream? Something
like, to help people build a life they love while enjoying the
journey along the way or something like that.”

Simon: “Bit corporate.”

Me: “Yeah.”

Simon: “I get it, by the way, because I know you and I love your
content - for years I’ve been watching it - so I genuinely do. If
I was doing this as an exercise with you, first of all you’ve got
an answer better than most and you’ve got to articulate it for
your business because you’ve got a team of people that have to
follow.”

Me: “Yeah like this is basically the business mission statement
cos I spent bloody ages trying to figure out, like, what’s the
thing.”

Simon: “Let’s make it personal for a second, right? Let’s go back
to younger you. This has really got to come from a younger you
point of view, I think. And again, I don’t know everything about
your life but the dream would be something like, when I was
younger, I always thought I was going to be a certain thing. But
then I realised, I could be anything. I don’t have to do this
selling time thing. I realised that the time selling thing was
the wrong way to think, and although I like being a doctor, it
was too much time in something that wasn’t going to scale. And I
woke up and I realised that I shouldn’t be selling time, and now
I need to tell everybody else what I’ve learnt. I’ve got to tell
everyone I know about this now, because I had the most glamorous
job. Most people dream of having that title and I don’t even use
it anymore, because I threw away the title. I didn’t care about
image. I just wanted to do something I enjoyed every day, and I
wanted to use my time to help other people do the same.”

Me: “Yep.”

Simon: “You’ve distilled it into a corporate version, right? As
you have to by the way. And I think company mission and personal
mission can be different. So my my personal mission is to fix the
education system. Company mission is to help people for free help
people, right, which is slightly different but that’s one tool to
fix the education system as far as I’m concerned. But my mission
and the company mission can be different, but my mission has to
come from a personal place and I think it has to be told in that
way too.”

Me: “Okay, with that in mind, let me try something else. Can you
ask me the question?”

Simon: “Okay, what’s your dream?”

Me: “So, when I was 17, I read a book that changed my life - The
4-Hour Work Week - and it taught me that I didn’t have to trade
my time for money. It also taught me to really think about where
I was going in life and whether that destination would bring me
happiness. I was working towards being a doctor, I went through 6
years of med school, I worked as a doctor for 2 years, and in
that time, I was able to build a business that allowed me to
become financially free, meaning that I was able to quit my job
and basically do what I love. And now, I look forward to Mondays
in a way that I never did when I had a day job. And the impact
that that book had on me, just putting me onto this trajectory,
helping me realise it was possible to become free in this way,
that’s what I want for other people. And so my dream, if I were
to distill it, would be something like to help people become
free. I’ve been toying with this idea of help people go from zero
figure entrepreneurs to four figure entrepreneurs, like, that
starting point.”

So, you might be wondering what the relevance is to productivity
with all this talk of dreams and missions.

Well, the “what’s your dream?” question might seem broad but it’s
actually really useful in working out your vision and direction
in life.

And asking these very broad, long-term questions is not just a
useful journalling exercise, it's one of the absolute critical
pillars of productivity, because you can be super efficient with
your work and spend years working towards something… only to
realise that you’re not going in the right direction after all.

An analogy I often use with this is thinking about a sports car -
you can have a really fast vehicle but if you don’t know where
you’re going or, even worse, you’re driving in the wrong
direction, you’re not actually being effective or productive.

And that’s exactly why I built LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho769n0bmhzp70444flhogk0v/qvh8h8ud0gpon3fg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9uXzMwJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) around two pillars - Action and Vision.

While action is all about building systems around your
productivity, the vision piece is all about getting crystal clear
on what actually matters to you, so you can create a path that
truly reflects who you are and where you want to go.

And when you figure this out, you’ll find that you your work
feels a lot more intentional and you’ll actually start making
consistent progress towards your goals.

If that sounds like something you’d find helpful, you can check
out LifeOS here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho769n0bmhzp70444flhogk0v/qvh8h8ud0gpon3fg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9uXzMwJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) and join over 2,000 other people who've taken steps towards
building a more sustainable productivity system.

And if you’ve got a moment today, have a think about Simon’s
question - what is your dream? 🤔

Have a great week ahead 🚀

Ali xx

column7: To-Do Lists Are Broken (Here’s The Solution)
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you had a good weekend 🙌

Quick thing before we start, today’s a big day for us as we’re
launching our next app 🥳 It’s called Momentum: Energising Habits
(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/m2h7h6u38k5mgqbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcy90b2RvOQ==
) and it’s focussed on helping you stay consistent with your
habits plus leverage the power of accountability through our
"Squads" feature. I’ve talked about the importance of energy and
accountability a lot in this newsletter, especially as it relates
to personal productivity, and Momentum’s (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/m2h7h6u38k5mgqbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcy90b2RvOQ==
) been built on this philosophy to help you stay consistent and
achieve more. You can download it here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/m2h7h6u38k5mgqbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcy90b2RvOQ==
). Check it out and let me know what you think 🙏

Anyway, on with the newsletter and today I wanted to address one
of the banes of my productivity - and a problem that a lot of you
guys seem to have as well - which is just having an endless list
of things I want to do and, more importantly, knowing how to
prioritise to get anything done 😅

In all seriousness, with an infinitely long to-do list, it’s very
easy to feel overwhelmed and do absolutely nothing, or, if you’re
a high achiever and lean more towards the “productivity bro” side
of things, you try and do everything at once which doesn’t
usually leave you feeling energised by the end of the day.

Back during lockdown, I definitely learned this the hard way. I
remember thinking, “excellent, I’ve got all this time - I’m going
to take guitar lessons and singing lessons and piano lessons and
I want to learn some Japanese on the side.” Looking back, it was
ambitious…

And I was just doing too much stuff and making minimal progress
in a thousand different directions instead of meaningful progress
in a few.

One of the things I really love about Oliver Burkeman’s
philosophy from Four Thousand Weeks is where he articulates that
there’s always simply too much shit to do and you’ll never have
enough time and energy for all of it. The solution, instead, is
to make strategic sacrifices.

And the way I personally do this is with what I call the Energy
Investment Portfolio (EIP).

I really like the financial terminology here because it feels
kind of fun and I love the whole money side of things, but it’s
also called the EIP because, just as we invest our money into
assets that hopefully compound over time (stocks, real estate,
crypto etc.), we can also think about investing our energy into
projects that compound.

And the EIP is basically a glorified to-do list, but it helps me
keep track of the things I’m choosing to invest my energy into
and the things I’m choosing to ignore.

Here’s how it works:

List A: The Dream List - This is your very long bucket list of
things you’d like to do at some point, including all your big
dreams and ambitions. You might not be able to do them right now
in this current season of life, but they’re worth capturing
somewhere.

List B: Active Investments - These are the projects you’re
actively investing energy into right now. And by “right now”, I
mean this week.

So the question I like to ask myself is: “What progress can I
make on this thing this week?”

A lot of people like to make long lists of action points for each
project but that’s often just its own exercise in procrastination
and so it’s important to really focus in on the next action
rather than trying to map everything out.

For the EIP to work, it’s also super important to limit your
active investments to around 3 - 5 projects.

Why? Because even though having lots of active investments makes
us feel ambitious and productive, the reality is that if we have
too many projects on the “active investment” list, our attention
and energy is divided across too many projects and we fail to do
any one of them well.

(Interestingly, this number also aligns with research (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/7qh7h2u9ovlwkmc9/aHR0cHM6Ly9wbWMubmNiaS5ubG0ubmloLmdvdi9hcnRpY2xlcy9QTUMyODY0MDM0Lz91dG1fc291cmNlPWNoYXRncHQuY29t
) on working memory showing that we can generally hold about 3-5
chunks of information in our brain’s “RAM” at any given moment.)

Now, as a bonus, you can also have a “passive investments” list.
These are projects that are on autopilot or that someone else is
taking care of.

For example, going to the gym used to be an active investment for
me when I had to motivate myself three times a week to life heavy
things. But now that I have a personal trainer who just tells me
“Monday, Wednesday, Friday” and I show up, it’s become passive.
I’m still investing energy when I’m actually working out, but the
mental energy of planning and motivating myself has been removed.

The biggest benefit of this system is that it forces you to be
honest about your capacity and make conscious choices about where
your energy goes. And when you focus your energy on fewer things,
you actually start making the kind of progress that feels
meaningful.

I take this concept further in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/owhkhwuwr39gk8sq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWVpcF85JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) and zoom out a bit with what I call Quarterly Quests - choosing
one main quest and up to 3 side-quests to work on for 90 days,
which are all aligned with your goals and vision for the future -
it’s the same principle but just on a specific time horizon.

So if you’re feeling like you’re constantly dealing with
overflowing to-do lists and struggling to manage your time, try
making those lists and your own Energy Investment Portfolio, let
me know how you get on.

(You can also turn some of those projects into habits that you
can track in Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/m2h7h6u38k5mgqbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcy90b2RvOQ==
) and work with others to stay on track with each one 👀 Just a
reminder, you can check it out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/m2h7h6u38k5mgqbl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcy90b2RvOQ==
)).

Have a great week and speak soon :)

Ali xx

Update Your Email Preferences (
https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26
) | Unsubscribe from ProductiveNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6dkprza9hzpl8333hwhz0g26/owhrrvo0hwuwr39gk4aq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NvcnJ5LXRvLXNlZS15b3UtZ28_cHJvZHVjdGl2aXZ0eWxhYg==

column7: Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. - Final Deadline Tomorrow!
column9:
July 15

                                      July 15 final deadline for Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. Program                                    





                                      Final Application Deadline:
                                      Tomorrow, July 15, 2025                                    


                                      Dear Candace,

                                      Thank you for your interest in the University of Pennsylvania Graduate School of Education.

All applications and required materials for the Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. program must be submitted to the Office of Admissions and Financial Aid no later than 11:59 pm (ET) tomorrow, Tuesday, July 15, 2025, to guarantee faculty review. If your application materials are received after this deadline, we will not be able to consider your application for the Fall 2025 term.
                                                                           

                                      If you have any questions about the application process or would like to have a conversation about potential study at GSE with one of our team's leaders, contact us <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/admissions/information> by email at admissions@gse.upenn.edu or by phone at (215) 898-6415.

                                      We look forward to reviewing your application!

                                      Sincerely,

                                      Leslie M. Levin
                                      Vice Dean of Admissions and Student Affairs
                                      University of Pennsylvania Graduate School of Education
                                      3700 Walnut Street, Philadelphia, PA 19104
                                      (215) 898-6415 | admissions@gse.upenn.edu





UNIVERSITY OF PENNSYLVANIA GRADUATE SCHOOL OF EDUCATION

                                      3700 Walnut Street
                                      Philadelphia, PA 19104

column7: Is your intuition smarter than your spreadsheets? (Mine was)
column9:
Hey friends,

You might’ve noticed (actually tbh you probably haven’t lol) that
I haven’t sent an issue of this newsletter in a few weeks. In
August I was visiting London with Izzy and our baby, and decided
to take a break from “content stuff” to be able to hang with
family and friends without the “pressure” of production
schedules. It felt great. We’re back in Hong Kong now, and so I’m
ramping up back into the work stuff, while also enjoying how
baby’s growing up and becoming much more interactive and fun
compared to when she was a potato-like creature who didn’t do
much other than cry and poop and sleep. Now she smiles reliably
(super cute), and actually seems to enjoy being taken for walks,
but seems to need more and more mental stimulation or she gets
restless.

Couple of quick things before we continue:

* Firstly, very exciting news because we’re officially launching
our next app Momentum: Energising Habits (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwzdzeulun6gpxxxh8h4lw6v/58hvh8ug5eernof7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2xpZmVub3Rlcy9pbnR1aXRpb24=
) this week 🥳 The app is focussed on helping you stay consistent
with your habits and leverage the power of accountability to make
meaningful progress on your goals. We’ll be officially announcing
it tomorrow but you can access it early here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwzdzeulun6gpxxxh8h4lw6v/58hvh8ug5eernof7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2xpZmVub3Rlcy9pbnR1aXRpb24=
) - check it out and let me know what you think 🙏
* Secondly, we’ll be hosting our usual quarterly reset workshop
on Saturday 20th September. This is a great opportunity to review
the last 90 days but, more importantly, set yourself up for
success for the final 100 days of the year. It’s a free event -
you can register by just clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwzdzeulun6gpxxxh8h4lw6v/e0hoq0pks0u7kxx8l2b7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbg==
).

Anyway, this week I wanted to share a reflection prompt I came
across from a business mentor.

I’ll describe the prompt as it relates to business, but you can
substitute for anything else in your life.

Think about how you FEEL about your business, on a scale of 0 to
10. Zero is “this is the worst feeling in the world, it’s going
terribly”, and 10 is “I feel amazing about my business, it can’t
possibly be any better”. Got a number in mind? Okay good. Now
imagine that number increases by 1. So if, for example, you were
a 5/10, imagine that in a hypothetical future, you feel 6/10 good
about it. In that 6/10 world, what does your business look like?
Don’t think too hard about this - just based on your gut
intuition, what’s happening in the business to make it feel 6/10?
Okay great, now add 1 more. So let’s imagine it’s a 7/10 in terms
of how you feel about it. Again, just based on your gut
intuition, what’s happening in the business to make you feel this
way about it?
My mentor guided me through the exercise - in my case, I’d chosen
6/10 as my original feeling. I was surprised to find that I
easily, and immediately, knew EXACTLY what would be different if
I felt 7/10 good about it, and if I felt 8/10 good about it.
Without any “thinking” that went into that, I intuitively knew
what it would look like. I said as much.

Okay great, now what you envision when we take your current
feeling and +2 to it, that’s going to form the exact vision we’re
going to work towards.
This is a… different… way of coming up with business goals than
I’ve ever tried before. Sure, I’ve done visualisation type
exercises where you project forward 3 years, and think about what
would be cool to have accomplished etc. And I’ve done loads of
journaling prompts based around: “What would the business look
like if I didn’t care about money” or “What would the business
look like if I could only get customers through referrals” and
stuff like that.

But this was the first time I’ve done something that was so
clearly “just” about “intuitive feeling” rather than
thinking-based exploring. And I was pleasantly surprised by how
clear my responses were.

The details are a little too “inside baseball” to share, but one
major theme that came up was how keen I am to have a physical
office for me and the Hong Kong-based team to work from. On
paper, this doesn’t make much sense - we could easily work from
our apartment (which we do sometimes), or from a co-working space
(which we also do sometimes), and pretty much everything we do
could be done remotely. But… there’s something that feels really
good and vibey about having an in-person office setup. We had
something similar back in 2021/2022 and it was super fun -
expensive, but super fun. And we had something sort-of similar in
2023 when I rented a massive apartment in Marylebone, London, and
we turned the living room into a co-working space, and converted
one bedroom into a YouTube studio and one into a podcast studio.
Each day we’d have a handful of team members around - those were
great times too.

But even though it was super fun, it always felt hard to justify
the expense. So when we moved to Hong Kong, I was like: “everyone
does this remote thing, how hard can it be, it’s way more
economical to just use our apartment and have team members over
on certain days”. But… now with a baby in the mix, the “hey our
house has an open door policy, anyone rock up whenever you want”
doesn’t feel right anymore. So I’ve been thinking: “hmm should we
get a proper office” but been held back by “ah but it’s so
expensive, I can’t justify the ROI”.

At least not on paper. But… after doing the “intuitive feeling”
thing, I realised: “screw the ROI. I’d feel much better about
running this business if we had a nice vibey office and me and
the team worked from there in-person, rather than our current
remote work-from-home setup”. And as I’ve been writing about for
years, when you feel good about what you’re doing, you become
more productive… so even though the ROI isn’t clear right now,
I’m sure it’ll become clear over time. Or maybe that’s just a
cope, and maybe I just want to hang out with people in person
because it’s more fun, which is itself also fine.

So yeah, we’re now actively looking for office spaces in Hong
Kong. The prices are… eye-watering, as you’d expect in HK. But I
keep coming back to this idea that sometimes the “right” decision
isn’t the one that makes sense on a spreadsheet. Sometimes it’s
the one that makes you go “yeah, this feels good.”

The various insights prompted by the “+2 feeling” prompt have
made me think about how I make decisions more broadly. I love to
pretend I’m this rational creature who makes choices based on
data and logic. I’ll often create elaborate pros and cons lists,
build financial models, ask for advice from 17+ people. But then,
often, I just end up doing what I wanted to do anyway - what felt
right from the beginning.

I wonder if I’d save myself a lot of time and mental energy if I
just… trusted that feeling more? Not in a “yolo blow the money on
vibes” way, but in a “my intuition is also a form of data” way. I
read somewhere that your gut feeling is essentially your brain
processing years of experience and pattern recognition at a speed
your conscious mind can’t match… which sounds plausible.

The tricky part is distinguishing between “this feels right
because it aligns with my values and vision” versus “this feels
right because it’s comfortable and I’m avoiding something scary.”
So I’m not sure how seriously to take the “feelings”…

Anyway, I’m curious – if you did this exercise with something in
your life (doesn’t have to be business – could be your health,
relationships, creative projects, whatever), what would come up?
What would take you from wherever you are now to +2 on that
feeling scale? And more importantly, what’s stopping you from
just… doing that thing?

I’d love if you could hit reply and let me know :)

Have a great week!

Ali xx

P.S. If you’re in / familiar with Hong Kong, and know of any cool
office spaces that might work for a team of 6-8 people, let me
know! Ideally somewhere with good natural light and space for a
filming setup. Also ideally not so expensive that Angus our
general manager has a stroke.

​💭 Claude by Anthropic: My Go-To AI Assistant (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwzdzeulun6gpxxxh8h4lw6v/qvh8h8ud8xx946hg/aHR0cDovL2NsYXUuZGUvbGlmZW5vdGVz
)​
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Whether it’s coming up with video titles, working on YouTube
scripts, or writing my email newsletters, like this one, pretty
much everything I do comes down to writing.

And these days, Claude (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwzdzeulun6gpxxxh8h4lw6v/qvh8h8ud8xx946hg/aHR0cDovL2NsYXUuZGUvbGlmZW5vdGVz

column7: 💊 How I Do a Ward Round on My Projects Every Week
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’re well - just a quick reminder before we start, we’re
just one week away from the launch of the $1k Challenge - a
6-week, live programme running across August and September aimed
at helping you take your first steps on the path to financial
freedom. If that sounds interesting, you can join the waitlist
here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48v0mwilh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/wnh2h6uq37k2nptl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP2xtLWdhJTNGdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXdhcmRyb3VuZF8xNCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWls
).

Anyway, on with today’s email where I want to talk about ward
rounds and how I’ve incorporated that approach into my own
personal productivity system. Let me explain.

If you’re a doctor - or like me, you’ve had experience working as
a doctor - you’ll be all too familiar with the ward round, which
is something that happens in hospitals at the very start of each
day or shift.

Basically, you go around and check in with all the patients on
your ward, and for each one, you talk to them, look at their
notes, review their vital signs, blood test results, and then
figure out the next action step in their treatment plan.

Now you’re probably wondering, how does this apply if you’re not
a doctor?

Well, the reason I’m telling you this is because you can use this
exact same concept when it comes to managing your projects - or
Quarterly Quests, as I like to call them.

Every 90 days, I recommend choosing one main quest - the single
most important thing you want to move forward over the next few
months - along with 1–3 side quests (and if you joined our Summer
Reset (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48v0mwilh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/reh8h9umed3l4la6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3dhdGNoLXRoZS1zdW1tZXItcmVzZXQtd29ya3Nob3Av
) that we hosted a few weeks ago, you probably already know
exactly what yours are...hopefully 😅).

And contrary to what a lot of advice might say, the specific tool
you use really doesn’t matter. What’s far more important is
asking yourself these 3 questions, which is something I do every
week as one part of my Weekly Review:

1️⃣ Are all my quests arranged in priority order?

2️⃣ Does every quest have a clear next action step?

3️⃣ Does every quest have an up-to-date status?

These might seem super simple, and they are, but let’s talk about
why I ask each of these questions specifically.

First things first, I always make sure my projects are arranged
in order of priority. Why? Because productivity isn’t about doing
everything - it’s about doing the right things in the right
order.

Secondly, and as David Allen talks about in Getting Things Done (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48v0mwilh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/08hwhgu2ke96v3ip/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL0I2bmN3T0I=
), every project needs a clearly defined next action step, and
btw, “continue” is not sufficient as a plan.

I remember back in the day when I was working in hospitals,
doctors would often get annoyed if a colleague wrote “continue”
as the plan, because it’s not enough to just keep things ticking
along. Every day, there has to be at least one action that helps
move the patient one step closer to getting out of hospital, and
it’s exactly the same with our own projects.

On the other hand, “waiting for” can be a valid next step, as
long as it’s written down clearly.

Thirdly, it’s important to track the status of your quests, and I
use this super simple emoji system:

🟢 On-track

🟡 Off-track with a plan

🔴 Off-track without a plan

🥶 Paused for now

Asking yourself these 3 questions is a job that takes no more
than 30 seconds, but it’s a small job that your brain needs to
say, “oh yeah, I did intend to sign up for the gym,” or “oh yeah,
I did say I was going to launch my YouTube channel.”

Tbh, I’m always surprised by how many people just don’t do it,
but I know it’s very easy to forget these small yet powerful
habits that actually help us achieve our goals. Even I sometimes
forget, and when that happens, I end up being less consistent and
making less progress because I’m not keeping track of everything.

So if there's one thing I'd recommend doing before next Monday's
email, it's make sure that you do this process, ask these
questions and check that things are still in order with your
goals. If you're someone who forgets or finds it hard to stick to
this consistently, it's worth just adding a simple recurring
reminder into your calendar with these three questions. (One of
my team even has it set up as an automation shortcut on his
iPhone that just runs at a set time each week).

If you want to find out what my entire Weekly Review process
looks like, then you can find the full set of questions as well
as others systems and strategies that you can use to make real
progress on your biggest goals within LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48v0mwilh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/8ghqh3uoxd26zrcl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXdhcmRyb3VuZF8xNCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
) - check it out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h48v0mwilh87pxrkkc4h8opl6/8ghqh3uoxd26zrcl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXdhcmRyb3VuZF8xNCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
). You'll join over 2,000 students who've already taken that step
to get clarity over their goals, control over their time and
systems to make progress.

Speak soon ☺️

Ali xx

column7: Ready to reset before the last 100 days of 2025?
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you’re having a great week 🙌

This is just a quick email to remind you that you’ve only got 48
hrs to register for the Autumn Reset Workshop which is happening
this Saturday at 1400 BST.

You can register for the event by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h5l7rxmbohpl5rkkkh9hnplgo/wnhv2x5pf6uqwx7n5nil/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
).

Next week, there’ll only be 100 days left in 2025 and the
workshop will be concentrated on making sure you’ve set yourself
up for success over these final few months of the year.

I love hosting these events and people always seem to get value
from them (here are some testimonials (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h5l7rxmbohpl5rkkkh9hnplgo/l2heh6ul362e02sg/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXN0aW1vbmlhbC50by9hbGktZXZlbnRzL2FsbA==
)), so it’d be great if you can join us.

Don’t wait until January to start making progress on your goals 👀

Hope to see you on Saturday 😊

Ali x

https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h5l7rxmbohpl5rkkkh9hnplgo

column7: New in Cursor: Plan Mode, Slash Commands, and more
column9:
Hello,

It’s been a busy month with new features and quality-of-life improvements to Cursor!

*********
Plan Mode
*********

Plan Mode ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/planning#plan-mode ) does deep research into your codebase, reading files and asking clarifying questions to create a detailed plan before writing any code. You can review and refine the plan before handing it to Cursor to execute.

We’ve found that this allows agents to run for significantly longer.

**************
Slash Commands
**************

You can now create reusable prompts and quickly share them with your team. Commands ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/chat/commands ) are stored in .cursor/commands/[command].md. Run them by typing /  in the Agent input and selecting the command from the dropdown menu.

We’ve been using them for running linters, fixing compile errors, and creating PRs with detailed descriptions and conventional commits.

****************
Browser Controls
****************

Agent can control a web browser ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/browser ) to test applications, audit accessibility, convert designs into code, and more. With full access to console logs and network traffic, Agent can debug issues and automate comprehensive testing workflows.

Start using with @Browser.

************************
PR Summaries from Bugbot
************************

When creating a PR in GitHub, Bugbot ( https://cursor.com/bugbot ) will now generate a summary of the changes. The summary will be updated as you push changes so it's always up-to-date.

Let us know any feedback you have!

- Cursor Team

Unsubscribe ( https://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgT_pwsDAIyumRWLrpkVAZnfEQZzsHNPnEyqTlRLog== )

column7: How to Maximise the Final 100 Days of 2025
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you had a good weekend 🙌

We’ve been settling into our new office over the past week and
it’s been so energising having somewhere to work in-person with
the team again. Of course we’ve done co-working in different
places since we moved to Hong Kong, but actually having your own
dedicated space just feels different. I’m such an advocate of
doing stuff in person anyway from an energy and accountability
perspective that I just know it’s going to make a difference to
my own productivity and the business overall.

But anyway, enough about my love for our new office (😅)…if you
didn’t know, we’re now just 100 days away from the end of 2025
and last Saturday, I hosted our regular quarterly reset workshop
where we were not only reflecting on the past quarter but setting
goals and ambitions for the final few months of the year.

Even though I host these sessions every quarter, I always find
the one in September particularly important. Why? Well, because
at this time of year it’s so easy to fall into the trap of
thinking “meh, January’s just around the corner - I’ll just wait
until then to make changes to my habits and set my goals for
2026”. And I’ve done this before too - New Year’s Resolutions
feel so tangible but delaying on setting those goals or adopting
new habits is really just a somewhat unsubtle form of unnecessary
procrastination (thinking about it, it's probably the most common
form of procrastination 😅).

So I always like to put particular emphasis on this September
reset and make sure that I’m not delaying any changes in the hope
that the New Year will bring more discipline, willpower or
motivation.

And I’d encourage everyone else to do the same. If you’ve ever
joined one of these sessions, you’ll know that they’re not
lectures, they’re far more interactive and given how much value
people get from attending, I wanted to share a few of the prompts
in this email to help everyone make the most of the final few
months of the year, rather than waiting until January 👀

So here are seven prompts that’d be useful to reflect on as we
head into the final 100 days of 2025:

* What’s one thing you’re doing that feels like you’re just going
through the motions?
* What would someone who really knows you say you should focus on
more?
* If you could only make meaningful progress on ONE work-related
thing in the final 100 days of 2025, what would most positively
impact your professional life?
* If you could only make meaningful progress on ONE personal
thing in the final 100 days of 2025, what would most positively
impact your personal life?
* If you had to create a plan to achieve those two goals, what
would it look like?
* And what daily or weekly habits / systems could you implement
to ensure consistent action across those final 100 days?
* If your future self could send you a text message right now,
what would it say?

Please do give these prompts some thought and write down your
answers if you can - I always find it easier to process and think
about these sorts of questions through writing or journalling.

And once you’ve got those notes and set your goals, make sure you
don’t just file it away until January - take steps to keep it
front of mind whether that’s by scheduling weekly reviews (as I
talk about in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvo8594ughv2edlllf9hplqro/kkhmh2unlv9nrmak/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTEwMF8yMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
)), or adding the goals to a reminder on your phone and set it to
go off every day or every week…just take some sort of action to
ensure that you’re regularly reminded of what you’re trying to
achieve.

This Goal, Plan, System (or GPS) framework has been
transformative for my own productivity - even within the
business, whenever we’re veering off course on a project, we
bring it back to GPS to work out where we’re falling down and 9
times out of 10, one of these three things has been neglected in
some way.

So give some thought to your own personal and professional goals
for the final 100 days, the plans you need to achieve them and
the systems/habits you need to put in place to make it all
happen. And if you want some accountability, feel free to hit
reply and let me know what you’re committing to doing (or
schedule an email to yourself to be sent on December 31st 👀).

I hope you find the prompts useful and if you want to watch the
full workshop, you can do so here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvo8594ughv2edlllf9hplqro/58hvh8ugm29gqlt7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi9hdXR1bW4tcmVzZXQtcmVwbGF5Lw==
).

Have a great week - talk soon!

Ali xx

Update Your Email Preferences (

) | Unsubscribe from ProductiveNotes (

column7: A question for Candace
column9:
Hey Candace,

 

If you’ve been searching for a way to make a difference your whole life…

 

If you finally feel ready to begin a new career that fulfills you…

 

I have an offer that’s going to change everything for you. ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-question-173-5&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+173-5&utm_content_name=A+question+for+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

 

Right now I’m searching for talented and passionate individuals with a deep desire for helping others and living life with purpose.

 

Jay Shetty Certification School ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-question-173-5&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+173-5&utm_content_name=A+question+for+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) is changing 1 billion lives through the power of intentional coaching, wisdom, and education.

 

As professional Life Coaches, we transform the world one person at a time by using evidence-based coaching methods to improve the emotional and mental well-being of our clients.

 

And we need people like you to make it happen.

 

Someone who understands their values and passions.

 

Someone who strives to be the best version of themselves every day.

 

Someone who is unafraid to use their talents to help the people around them.

 

If this sounds like you, click here to begin your coaching journey today ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-question-173-5&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+173-5&utm_content_name=A+question+for+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )!

 

I believe there’s nothing more fulfilling and meaningful than being a Life Coach.

column7: 🏭 The System Helping Me Make Better Videos (Copy This)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’re having a great week 🔥​​Before we dive into this
week’s CreatorNotes, I have a favour to ask. I'd love for you to
take 50 seconds to answer our Creator survey here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hp3r9e5b5h2qd6dllcnhp8ldx/z2hgh7uepeer36tz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoYW5rLXlvdS1iZi8_ZW1haWw9YWljb2FjaGluZzIwMjUlNDBnbWFpbC5jb20=
). It’ll help me make sure I’m sharing the most relevant stuff
with you. Thank you 😊

Anyway, I've mentioned in recent emails that Tuesdays are now set
aside as my one and only YouTube filming day of the week, and I
wanted to dive into all the details of what my current video
production pipeline looks like.

We talk a lot about systems in PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hp3r9e5b5h2qd6dllcnhp8ldx/p8hehqu4g445zoar/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1zeXN0ZW1zXzA1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
), to make staying consistent on YouTube a whole lot easier, but
my own system has changed quite a bit recently that I figured it
was worth sharing.

Over the years, I’ve been publishing 1-2 YouTube videos every
single week but a few months ago, I made the decision to drop
down to 1 video per week.

Why? Because when you're committed to hitting that twice-weekly
cadence on top of launching new apps and products within the
business, you inevitably start making compromises on video
quality. Not massive ones, but compromises large enough to make
you question whether the video is actually good enough.

Whereas if I committed to just a single video every week, the
theory was that I’d be able to raise the bar on quality and put
something out into the world that I was genuinely proud of.

Now just to caveat before I go any further - if you're just
getting started on YouTube, please don't worry about trying to
make everything perfect. I've been doing this thing for over 8
years now, and one of my core philosophies is that when you're
trying to get your channel off the ground, quantity is way more
important than quality.

But once you’ve got to a stage where your channel’s more
established, you can afford to be more selective with the content
you put out there.

On top of my change in upload frequency, there’s been an even
more interesting shift in where YouTube sits in my overall
identity and focus.

I've been calling myself a "YouTuber" for years now and it’s been
my primary identity in terms of how I spend my time and mental
energy.

But increasingly, I've been feeling this pull towards shifting
that identity to "entrepreneur” - not because I'm abandoning
YouTube (definitely not 🙈), but because I'm realising that the
work I find most energising right now is building products and
software that genuinely help people and scale beyond me just
talking to a camera.

So my new filming system involves thinking about YouTube on
Tuesdays only.

I pick one idea (shoutout to my producer, Becky, who does all the
heavy lifting on that front), spend some time preparing an
outline and usually a framework (because in educational videos,
having a unique framework massively increases the value of a
video rather than it just being a list of generic points), and
then I film.

Sometimes I'll write out the hook properly - usually by asking AI
to brainstorm a bunch of options, disliking all of them, and then
writing it myself anyway 😅 But for the main body of the video,
I'm mostly riffing off bullet points because this feels most
natural to me.

The only exception is when I'm creating a video based on a
conversation I've had, maybe with someone here in Hong Kong or
over a Zoom call. In those cases, Holly (my writer) will go
through the conversation, pull out the best soundbites, and
structure them into a logical flow, which I can then work off
within my filming session.

I also make sure to film any overhead shots or B-roll that day
too because the goal is to get at least one complete video from
each filming session. And tbh, it’s working way better than I
expected.

The video quality is higher (imo 😉), I'm enjoying the process
more, and crucially, I've got the mental space and time to focus
on building out the business side of things during the week.

Now, obviously this system works for me because I've got an
incredible team supporting the content creation process
throughout the week and I realise that most people reading this
don't have a full production team (yet!).

But the lesson here is that you can build systems that allow you
to batch your creative work, even if you're doing everything
yourself.

YouTube doesn’t have to be always on your mind if you want to do
it well, and building sustainable systems for content creation
that don't require you to be "on" 24/7 is a core focus within
PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hp3r9e5b5h2qd6dllcnhp8ldx/p8hehqu4g445zoar/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1zeXN0ZW1zXzA1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
).

The whole point of the course and community is to help you grow
your YouTube channel without it taking over your entire life, but
whether or not you join PTYA, I'd encourage you to think about
where in your own video production pipeline you could benefit
from batching your focus, like setting aside one morning for all
your planning and ideation or filming all your videos in one day
instead of spreading them throughout the week.

Have a think and let me know if you make any changes - hit reply
and send me an email.

Have a great week 😊

Ali xx

🚀 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hp3r9e5b5h2qd6dllcnhp8ldx/6qhehoulnll678f9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
).
