column7: 💬 Why I Start Every Day With Just One Question
column9:
Hey Candace,

As I mentioned last Monday, some of my old uni friends were here
in Hong Kong last week and we had a great time catching up,
including with some hikes up a couple of the many trails
overlooking the city. I don't often make time to walk up the
trails but it's a great way to add a bit of adventure into the
day.

And speaking of adventures (seamless segue 😜), I actually wanted
to talk about a single question that I ask myself at the very
start of each day pretty much without fail which has helped
transform my personal productivity and that is:

“What’s today’s adventure going to be?”

You may have heard me talk about it before but this simple habit
has been transformative for three main reasons:

1️⃣ It helps me focus on my most important task.

Your Daily Adventure is basically another way of framing your
most important task for the day (but I’ll get to why I call it an
“adventure” later).

In the book, Make Time (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/owhkhwuwnz0mzdaq/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3NpQlZLVA==
), which is where I first heard of this idea, they actually call
it the “Daily Highlight”.

And it could be a work-related thing, or it could be something as
simple as calling your grandma or playing football with your
kids.

But whatever it is, your Daily Adventure is the task that, when
done today, will make the biggest difference to your life.
Because if you just did that single, high-impact thing every day
for 365 days, you’d be totally winning at life and making a tonne
of progress towards your goals.

2️⃣ It removes decision fatigue.

Setting your Daily Adventure also saves you time and mental
energy.

It’s the first thing you should be doing whenever you have a bit
of spare time, and with your Daily Adventure at the forefront of
your mind, you’ll never find yourself thinking, “Wait… what was I
meant to be doing again?”

3️⃣ It makes your day more joyful.

The third main benefit of asking, “What’s today’s adventure going
to be?” is that framing a task as an adventure makes it feel way
more fun and energising.

As I talk about in Feel-Good Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/kkhmh2une7okg2ck/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2Fhd2Vic2l0ZQ==
), the single biggest productivity hack of all time is finding a
way to enjoy what you’re doing, and finding a way to generate
energy from that thing you’re doing.

So let’s say I need to finish making some slides as new course
material for LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/08hwhgu2x8p30esp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWFkdmVudHVyZV8yJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
), and it’s super important to get them done. I could think of it
as my most important task or my Daily Highlight. But thinking of
it as my Daily Adventure puts a totally different spin on it.

Maybe I could play some Harry Potter music in the background
while I’m making the slides, or go out to finish them at a local
coffee shop whilst also treating myself to a nice little matcha
latte (yes, it's my new go-to drink too).

These tiny tweaks might not sound like a lot, but trust me,
approaching something in the spirit of play - instead of always
taking everything really seriously - makes a huge difference to
your productivity and progress.

Besides your Daily Adventure, you can also give yourself 3
optional side quests to complete on any given day.

These are fun, short-term goals that run alongside the bigger
stuff you’ve got going on, and I like to choose one for work, one
for health, and one for relationships.

For example, my adventure might be filming a video about how I
use AI as a life coach (which I actually released on Saturday -
watch it here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/z2hgh7ue7gmq49hz/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9RRjJ3SXl3dkRoaz9zaT1LRkU3dmxQalBqZ1BHY3hX
)). And then my side quests could be writing this email
newsletter, going to the gym and having a date night with Izzy. 🥰

I do all of this as part of something I call my Morning
Manifesto, which I teach all my students inside LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/08hwhgu2x8p30esp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWFkdmVudHVyZV8yJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

The Morning Manifesto is a 5-minute checklist that sets you up
for a productive, joyful day, and you can think of like
journalling, but it’s just a lot faster and made up of 3
components: Prime, Align, and Organise.

We go into each of these in a lot more detail within the course,
but your Daily Adventure falls into the Align category - and the
most important step is to make sure it’s scheduled in your
calendar.

That way, you’ll never waste time wondering what to do next and
you’ll always just get on with the one thing that actually
matters all while having fun, of course.

(If you want to dive deeper into my flagship productivity system,
you can learn more about LifeOS here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh67v7lguvhq2mvrrrho/08hwhgu2x8p30esp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWFkdmVudHVyZV8yJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
)).

I hope you enjoy the rest of your week (and set your Daily
Adventures 😉).

Speak soon :)

Ali xx

column7: [GoodBarber] Tip 8/9: Test your app
column9:
Hi ,

Before you submit your app to the stores and start spreading the word about it, it's always smart to run a few tests. 

This way, not only will you ensure that your app's user experience is optimal, but you can also rid your app of any remaining bugs or mistakes which might slow down the stores' review processes.

How can you test your GoodBarber app?

Beyond the back office preview,  there are several other preview options: 

My GoodBarber App

This app, available at  Android (https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.goodbarber.mygoodbarber), allows you to test a preview version of your app, on your Android device.

The ad hoc version

You can retrieve the ad hoc version once you've built your app, for iOS (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/0/69/).
We recommend using this version to perform tests before submitting your app to the stores, as it is the exact copy of the native application you will be submitting.

If you have any questions just write to the support (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/support/), we’d be glad to help you

We hope this will be useful!

Sincerely,
The GoodBarber support team

DO YOU NEED HELP? WE ARE HERE!

If you need help during the creation of your app, how do you proceed ?
- Watch our video tutorials which contain all our tips to get you started on creating your app  Click here (https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL9cDLx7GDOFskgb7sxkiAOtwGU-p4PuVR)!
- Checking the Online Help (https://candaceux.goodbarber.app/manage/settings/help/) documentation is always a great place to start, to find answers to all your questions and useful tutorials.
- If you're still stuck, simply open a ticket to the Unsubscribe from this list (https://goodbarber.com/unsubscribe/635744e4868e797a0cd865d25dc7cfef2f26ef80)

column9:

Device: Safari on macOS
Verification code: 970740

If you did not attempt to sign in to your account, your password may be compromised. Visit https://github.com/settings/security to create a new, strong password for your GitHub account.

If you'd like to automatically verify devices in the future, consider enabling two-factor authentication on your account. Visit https://docs.github.com/articles/configuring-two-factor-authentication to learn about two-factor authentication.

column7: Your purpose, Candace
column9:
What’s your purpose, Candace?

 

Most people don’t really know…

 

But I’ve found there’s a select group of people who know EXACTLY what it is - they know they were meant to serve others.

 

They may not know how.

 

But I know they are the most amazing people.

 

Who can create the most incredible impact.

 

In fact, they have the power to change thousands of lives…if they have the right “tools” in their “kit”. ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-purpose-174-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+174-2&utm_content_name=Your+purpose%2C+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

 

I’ve been lucky enough to learn those tools for myself.

 

And I’ve used them to impact so many lives around the world.

 

I finally live my purpose.

 

And I have so much joy in my life.

 

Now I want to share these tools with as many people as I can.

 

People who feel their purpose is to help and serve others.

 

But just need the right tools to help them do that.

 

If you want to be one of them - click here and I’ll help you get started today. column7: Candace: Welcome to IxDF New York City. Here's what to do next!
column9:
Interaction Design Foundation logo [https://public-images.interaction-design.org/emails/brand/v5/ixdf-logo-for-header.jpg]
 WELCOME TO IXDF NEW YORK CITY!
 Dawn Dinh [https://public-images.interaction-design.org/user-uploads/169919/profile-pictures/original.1706896416.png?tr=w-560,h-560] 
 

Your Local Leader of IxDF New York City is Dawn Dinh, who is CC-ed in this
email. Feel free to contact them (simply “Reply all” to this email) with
questions or ideas for IxDF New York City.

THIS IS YOUR OPPORTUNITY....
IxDF New York City
[https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyjFuxCAQAMDXQOcTrMHggiIN_4CFxUg2nDAXK7-P0qeeSW6nmMny7KTRK1iQAvjhAESWZtNEiTTqRKtAqaU2aVdrtDuvTslNGUIyQMZapbSwedsixS1FSaiYErXNPALO2tuS8l1Le_VR-OmOOd83W78YeAb-eZ7X_5WBPzuGcymjf94MfOtjHku48qgYGPhPqzOn5Z5h5vvPf5APFyr2gEdtBQRopkS5Qj1f2C_-7eA3AAD__1AjTiM] 
is not just a local group. It's a unique opportunity for you to make a
significant impact on your own career.

It's an opportunity for you to expand your network, learn new things, and engage
with a community passionate about great design.

It's up to you now! The more energy you invest, the more you gain: show up
consistently for meetups, schedule one yourself, or even volunteer as a Co-Local
Leader. There's so much you can do—and benefit from.

WHY ATTEND IXDF MEETUPS?
 * Your network is your net worth—join us to learn, network, and find
   opportunities.
 * Connect with professionals who can open new doors.
 * Be part of a community where small meetups lead to big opportunities.
 * Get help and advice from our community. And give back.
 * Come as you are! Design skills are not just for designers—they're for
   everyone in any job, any industry.
 * Be part of a caring and supportive community.
 * It's free for everyone to attend—so bring your friends who are not IxDF
   members.

WHAT'S NEXT? HERE'S YOUR CHECKLIST!
 1. First, introduce yourself to the group in the IxDF New York City
    conversation thread
    [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyjFuxCAQAMDXQOcTrMHggiIN_4CFxUg2nDAXK7-P0qeeSW6nmMny7KTRK1iQAvjhAESWZtNEiTTqRKtAqaU2aVdrtDuvTslNGUIyQMZapbSwedsixS1FSaiYErXNPALO2tuS8l1Le_VR-OmOOd83W78YeAb-eZ7X_5WBPzuGcymjf94MfOtjHku48qgYGPhPqzOn5Z5h5vvPf5APFyr2gEdtBQRopkS5Qj1f2C_-7eA3AAD__1AjTiM]
    .  * It's your first small step toward expanding your local network and
       experiencing the warmth of your community.
     * Your post allows your fellow members of IxDF New York City to get to
       know you, connect with you, and let opportunities find you.
     * interested in, struggling with, or need help with. Anything that'll allow
       the others to connect with you.
    
    
 2. Your post could spark lifelong friendships, and unexpected career
    opportunities!
 3. Add "Member of IxDF New York City" as a position on your LinkedIn profile.  * 
       This will both help build your credibility and bring more awareness to
       IxDF New York City.
     * 
       Here's an example
       [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJwUy0tuhiAQAODTwO43MPJywaIb7sFjRidVaMTU6zc9wNfiRgUpSIza2xUCaAXyiBtupVVsTSsDytpGHjM0ZQtlrdFJjkY746mSB_IhGGNVQOcKFdeKpmqEUdwfvHN9ePRPw8l7X8a9yzMez_MzxfolIAlI7_suJ_dvbNyXOi4BibuA1PM8Lj4_1yh5TrxZQJJ3zFxHrgf3HRRYYdR-ZT7_ofyN8BcAAP__-ZhB8w]
       .
    
    
 4. Additionally, write a post on your LinkedIn profile to announce that you're
    now a member of IxDF New York City.  * Invite your local connections to
       share suggestions on meetups they would find valuable.
     * Remember to link to IxDF New York City
       [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyjFuxCAQAMDXQOcTrMHggiIN_4CFxUg2nDAXK7-P0qeeSW6nmMny7KTRK1iQAvjhAESWZtNEiTTqRKtAqaU2aVdrtDuvTslNGUIyQMZapbSwedsixS1FSaiYErXNPALO2tuS8l1Le_VR-OmOOd83W78YeAb-eZ7X_5WBPzuGcymjf94MfOtjHku48qgYGPhPqzOn5Z5h5vvPf5APFyr2gEdtBQRopkS5Qj1f2C_-7eA3AAD__1AjTiM]
       .
    
    
 5. IxDF will comment, like, and boost your post when you tag the IxDF
    [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxkzLFyhCAQANCvgU4HVsBNQZHG_wCW1Z0o3HgmJn-fufraVzyKH5wro67Rzn4CBGtAb5E4EaFlxBo4T9aRA7Q-UTU-e8NaorPBzVx4Bp4RnfMGawiZc6BsuTjljLSrnqlc0ttA9SlrG_u56j1u1_V4qulTwaJgue973KV9VZI2ln4oWEo_Hqn9KVjkl3h4jwbu343SS_QZk5SeyiZtBQNeObMeSfbXpX8i_AcAAP__ZKNJ9g] 
    and use the hashtags #ixdf and #ixdflocalgroups.  * We'll do the same on
       other platforms: Instagram
       [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJwUyj1uxSAMAODTwNYIHCDuwNCFa1T8mVh6gYqgpsev3v4V_0mpEsrq9WF3QNAK5OmdKqjyHl3KFhEBi00lJbDKgcGiJXujnTko0wF0IBpjFVbnEiVXkqZshFHcV50xLx79o9SbW9_GbPLlz7V-brF_CQgCwvM8G_d7xTbjteVxCQj8V-h7zCYgyOkj5xHzyb2BAiuMalfk15vKXw__AQAA__8lxzyD]
       , Facebook

       , Threads
       [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJwUyDFuxSAMANDTwNYIHENgYOiSa1RgMEH6HyqCmh6_6vpy8JwKO1mCPswODrQCeQUTjfcUnXF-Zyw-GSLnlNVGR2b0sgXUFg8mPoAP5xCNcsXaxMnmpJlQoGp9lRlptdE_crlb7duYVb7Ctdb3LfZPAaeA83mebV2zxHxvvax_RNV-M3-NWQWccobYaES6Wq-gwAhU9R3ba6Pxlj8B_gIAAP__Vbs8WQ]
       , and X
       [https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJwUysFuwyAMANCvgdsq4ziGHTjskt-YwODEUhumFE39_Kr31_K31q7J9xziumDCAOiPHBtyiIsAiECtUnpFYhYtlHTh5i1TYIoqGlFjSkQrpM5ctXKrQYUcgZ2zX0WmjfOr9aft521cu7_nY86_p1t-HG4Ot9dNxsPhZq-mvx9w5WIyihx27gi4OoL9Uez-cf4_4zsAAP___Lw3uA]
       .
     * Where possible, use the
       hashtags #ixdf and #ixdflocalgroups so more people can find, and join,
       IxDF New York City. The more your group grows and thrives, the more 
       career opportunities you get. It's a positive feedback loop of win-win.
    
    
 6. I encourage you to arrange meetups in collaboration with your IxDF Local
    Leader.  * When you step up and arrange meetups in collaboration with your
       Local Leader, you ignite a spark of collective action and true community
       spirit.
     * Our most successful local groups hold a meetup on the very same day,
       every single month and share the responsibility. For their members,
       meetups become predictable and habit-forming. They become a monthly 
       self-empowering practice of networking and career growth.
     * As such, meetups are the heartbeat of IxDF New York City. They're not
       only the pulse of life of your group—they also reflect its very soul.
    
    
 7. Find out if there is an existing LinkedIn or Facebook group for IxDF New
    York City.  * If yes, then connect!
    
    
 8. Consider volunteering as a Co-Local Leader of IxDF New York City.  * You
       could help make an impact — especially on your own career.
     * You may
       have connections, great ideas, and access to resources other members
       don't.
     * When
       you help drive collective success, you earn the credibility as a true
       leader and build lifelong connections.
    
    
 9. Say hi to your Local Leader(s) (CC'ed on this email)!

Go to IxDF New York City
[https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyjFuxCAQAMDXQOcTrMHggiIN_4CFxUg2nDAXK7-P0qeeSW6nmMny7KTRK1iQAvjhAESWZtNEiTTqRKtAqaU2aVdrtDuvTslNGUIyQMZapbSwedsixS1FSaiYErXNPALO2tuS8l1Le_VR-OmOOd83W78YeAb-eZ7X_5WBPzuGcymjf94MfOtjHku48qgYGPhPqzOn5Z5h5vvPf5APFyr2gEdtBQRopkS5Qj1f2C_-7eA3AAD__1AjTiM]

[https://email.mailgun.interaction-design.org/c/eJxsyrGOhCAQANCvgU4jwwhsQXGN_wHDDJKsukFy_v41V2778kp8SWYJmqPxq4UAZgG9R0zeWAPBWHSvQqlANikJBYLsyIJuEY1DLyQexIeAuC6BncuSXclGCBUu7RzcE412nVPhu9VzvnrV77iP8bmV_VGwKdie55m_VwXbwUfmfivYKo9JOvP0T3v76B5ToyvR3s4KC6wKl3qk9p7pOvRvhL8AAAD__4udR1s] 
and build your credibility at the same time. Yes, really! 

Best regards, Mads Soegaard [https://public-images.interaction-design.org/emails/signatures/mads.png]

column9:

Learn In-Demand AIML Skills to Land $300K+ Roles - Register Now (https://d1KhQf04.na1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/GF+113/d1KhQf04/VWW2XM4jZD-NW7tQ16q4NHswwW8hW1h35DS6DjN1WCR-q5fr76W5BWr2F6lZ3pfW1yxlh62SW31sW4bFdFC5dD6KQW1GPMnN75Cr44W1n9LVt8-8yQ_N33rWmTl_DYDW51-n_S3BPy8YW4RJ0fS6MmRP_W3FkrcN96C-pXW5NdLZ84MPz8SW3hxcG-7T-yGsMckhTWwn8pCW3ks8nJ54136JW7mRZWT7-b8hqW2XsNT74mlDbGW27C6qc7VSCx-W4_K0CB9hc_VNW66LDsW1VYrpfW3F0zvS490_rrW8sRw5G6lG0sMW1dm6kx4fmNbtN37fqdRbcGJsVgn1mG2GZ3HfW4jPX8p2FgX79W5g9vXG88z_wjW1pkvVQ50GHJhW6LRJZh8NJKw7W6VXNqw6WLCDYVmS8hz4TzHglV5ffVj2bdJj5V_0tXC1y3GRKW5hkFLM1zYy16W79D9Kn1-V4skW4HzD7K77SPCBW59kVXr4R8gjnf1c1mcv04 )



Hi Candace,

AI isn’t the future… it’s the NOW. And tech professionals like you are at the perfect point to ride this wave.

Don’t let the AI revolution pass you by. Register for our Introductory AI/ML Session and discover how AI skills can set you apart in an ultra-competitive tech job market.

Here’s what you’ll learn in the webinar:



💸 AI vs. Tech Salaries

Uncover why AI/ML roles offer massive salary boosts compared to traditional tech jobs and how you can tap into this growing demand.

🎯 The Right Program for Your Next Step

Whether it’s specialized Machine Learning skills, AI-powered app building, or integrating AI into your coding workflow, we’ll help you chart the right path.

column7: 5 Lessons From 8 Years on YouTube
column9:
Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - in case you missed it, we’re
launching the $1k Challenge tomorrow (Mon 21st July) - a live
6-week programme that I’m hosting from 1st Aug to 12th Sept. If
you’re a beginner to making money online, and you like the idea
of working towards financial independence someday, then I’d love
for you to join the waitlist (here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/48hvh7umnxnkgvhq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP2xtLWdhJTNGdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1saWZlbm90ZXMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXl0bGVzc29uc18yMCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWls
)) and be amongst the first to hear when things launch tomorrow.

Secondly, big thank you to everyone who replied to last week’s
email with more Harry Potter fan fiction recommendations. Just
reading those will tide me over for the next few weeks at least
:) If you’re interested, the recommendations were: Manacled (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/wnh2h6uq3038g7cl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlLm9yZy9kZXRhaWxzL21hbmFjbGVkXzIwMjQxMg==
) (thanks Shireen), Innocent (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/reh8h9ume6enxzi6/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmFuZmljdGlvbi5uZXQvcy85NDY5MDY0LzEvSW5ub2NlbnQ=
) (thanks Brian), Oh God Not Again (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/08hwhgu2klkqz5fp/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlb2ZvdXJvd24ub3JnL3dvcmtzLzQ3MDE4NjkvY2hhcHRlcnMvMTA3MzYzNjY=
) + The Arithmancer (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/8ghqh3uoxrxk96sl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlb2ZvdXJvd24ub3JnL3dvcmtzLzE0MjgxNDQwP3ZpZXdfZnVsbF93b3JrPXRydWU=
) (thanks Shaurya), Harry Potter and the Problem of Potions (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/vqh3hmuodwd8gzaw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlb2ZvdXJvd24ub3JnL3dvcmtzLzEwNTg4NjI5L2NoYXB0ZXJzLzIzNDA0MzM1
) + Dwelling (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/l2heh6ulzxzwrxbg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudHVtYmxyLmNvbS9mcm9zdHktdm1jLzE3OTMyMzkxODYxMC9kd2VsbGluZy1jaGFwdGVyLTEtYWlkZW9tYWktaGFycnktcG90dGVy
) (thanks Clarice), The Darkness Within (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/m2h7h6u3747welsl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmFuZmljdGlvbi5uZXQvcy8yOTEzMTQ5LzEvVGhlLURhcmtuZXNzLVdpdGhpbg==
) (thanks Mohammed-Hadi).

Anyway, this month marks eight years since I started properly
making videos on YouTube. That’s literally as long as I spent in
medicine (6 years at med school + 2 years as a doctor). Looking
back, there are some things I wish someone had told me at the
beginning - I suspect they apply to any creative thing you might
like to do.

1. You don’t need a grand plan to get started

8 years ago, I had no master plan. No grand vision. No carefully
crafted strategy about hitting six million subscribers or
building a business empire.

I just thought it might be fun to make videos, I’d been wanting
to try YouTube for ages, and I thought that if I made videos
about how to pass the BMAT medical admission test, some % of
viewers might think I’m legit and sign up to my BMAT course.

I set myself the goal of: “I’m just going to make 1 video a week
for 2 years and then we’ll see what happens”.

In hindsight, I think this lack of a plan was an advantage. If
I’d tried to map out some perfect five-year plan, I never would
have started because it would have felt overwhelming and probably
wrong anyway. How could I have possibly predicted where things
would go?

There’s this line from Rumi that I love: “When you walk the way,
the way will appear.” You just have to take one step, then
another, and the path becomes clearer as you go.

2. 95% of people never start, and most who do don’t keep going

The stats for podcasts are interesting - more than 80% of
podcasts have fewer than 3 episodes. Less than 1% have more than
20 episodes. I suspect, based on 5 years of teaching our
Part-Time YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhnoo628i3i89xm400cgh3d27w/dphehmuempmr5xtl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXl0bGVzc29uc18yMCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bGlmZW5vdGVz
) course, that YouTube channels are similar. Loads of people
THINK about maybe starting a YouTube channel someday. Almost none
(in the grand scheme of things) actually make their first video.
And of those that do make their first video, almost none make
more than 20.

So the game is actually quite simple: just get started, then just
keep going.

I think people get stuck on the first part because they’re
addicted to certainty. If you’ve spent your life following clear
career paths (medicine, law, accounting, whatever), the idea of
doing something without a clear yellow brick road to follow feels
terrifying. What if it goes nowhere? What if you put all this
time and effort into something and it doesn’t materialise in CV
points?

When it comes to creative-type things like YouTube, there are no
guarantees. There’s certainly a lot you can do to stack the deck
in your favour, but the lion’s share of the work is: get started,
keep going, make micro adjustments as you go, do it for ages.

3. External motivation only gets you so far

For the first few years, making money from YouTube was incredibly
motivating. But after a while, money stops being a reliable
source of energy. In fact, when I focus too much on the money, it
actually sucks the motivation out of everything.

What keeps me going now? Two C’s: connection and contribution.

The connection I get from comments, DMs, people coming up to me
in the street saying the content helped them, people attending
the in-person events we host - that feels meaningful in a way
that money doesn’t.

And the feeling of contribution, the feeling that the stuff I
make and stick on the internet might be actually helping people -
that becomes the thing that gets me out of bed in the morning and
continuing to do this.

4. Even fun things become work (so you’ve got to keep making them
fun)

Being a YouTuber sounds amazing from the outside. And it is. But
like anything you do professionally, even the most enjoyable
things start feeling like work after a while.

The key is constantly finding new wells of enjoyment. When video
editing stopped being fun, I found other aspects to get excited
about. When working remotely got boring, I hired people in-person
(even though it’s more expensive) because it made the process
more enjoyable.

Sometimes I make videos that I know won’t get as many views
because they’re more fun for me to create. Even other aspects of
our business, like this weekly email newsletter - it’s not
optimised for maximum engagement, or for maximum advertising, or
trying to forcibly “convert” you into becoming a paid customer…
but it’s fun to do, and it’s nice to get replies when I gush
about Harry Potter fan fiction, so I keep doing it.

You’ve got to be okay with leaving money on the table sometimes.
The happiest creators I know are the ones who sometimes choose
fun over finances.

5. You never know how things will turn out

Eight years ago, if you’d told me I’d be a full-time YouTuber,
bestselling author, have the freedom to work from anywhere, make
enough money to not worry about money, and genuinely love what I
do for work - I would’ve had a stroke and a hernia at the same
time.

Jeff Bezos has this great analogy: in baseball, the maximum you
can score is four points (a home run). But in business, there’s
no upper limit - if something works, you could get a million
points or a billion points. If something works, it can completely
transform your life in ways you never imagined.

I tried seven different business ideas before YouTube. Six were
complete failures, one was moderately successful. But YouTube has
been a home run that’s unlocked everything else.

The thing is, you never know which swing is going to be the one
that changes everything. You just have to keep taking shots.

Concluding Thoughts

If there’s something you want to try - a creative project, a side
business, learning a new skill - just start.

Don’t wait for the perfect plan or the perfect moment.

And once you start, commit to sticking with it longer than feels
comfortable. Most people quit right before things get
interesting.

I couldn’t have imagined keeping this going for 8 years when I
got started. But now 8 years feels like rookie numbers. We’re
just getting started :)

Have a great week!

Ali xx

Hey Premium Ghostwriters, happy Monday!

Quick reminder:

Tomorrow, October 28th at 9 AM PST, I'll be going live with my next free Masterclass:

The 4 Things You MUST Do Differently To Land Premium Clients In 2026

I'll walk through 4 important frameworks you need to understand to land high-ticket clients (which 99% of writers don’t even know exist yet).

During the session, I'll break down:

• The biggest mistake ghostwriters make when using AI (and how to avoid it so you can reliably use AI in your ghostwriting business).

• How to attract dream (and high-paying) clients so you can finally scale your income as a writer.

• The simple way to automate 80% of your outreach, research, AND fulfillment so you don't burn yourself out building your business.

And tons more.

I'm putting the finishing touches on an exclusive bonus for everyone who attends live—a brand new resource that'll make leveraging AI in your writing business 10x easier.

But you have to show up live to get it.

This alone should save you dozens of hours of trial and error (and honestly, a lot of frustration).

Click here to claim your free spot.

Chat soon,

Welcome to Google Workspace. Let's get started.

Complete setup and start using the premium features included in your plan.

Review your recommendations<https://c.gle/ANiao5ql8Hg16dM4i_Kp_pHZrX3vsk8SVZgQM0rPM3HZZ-B9EJ3-N_LPoeuHCaZirdPHv20NIXY6sHSW7TwatH7BmfuywlcUQKk8fLM6j9ULxsJxotVQp1f3nLTvBqKvkoWvOgC4kyYaIgDGBCpyOFQFKggx98u1XStlKKmfKn75utEMdfmrWQsETATEZ3R2Qshvfka269U4HQ>

Get Workspace set up for business

Visit the Workspace Admin console to:

- Upload your company’s logo, create email aliases (support@... orhelp@...), and add a company-wide email signature
- Add accounts for your team members
- Transfer emails, contacts, and calendars from other accounts
- Turn on 2-Step Verification to protect user accounts

Review your recommendations<https://c.gle/ANiao5qSeGpBpEy-b9SM8XM7nr7CUD2DWsFa9j9kVa1-4CGWVqdL-pYq69BIHO7Do5Kp5SlAGbZKp1mZCWovMtOjmwnae1tnm2-NeDiF2ewOd-kCyoyJrLr0koZAqEkSW-15puiWvMNrM3iqNhYt7bY8tfO5uKhn7aNuzaKNzmQppNvvkEpX3bS4vKphXDWGLum3FzfPAP51>

Your Gmail has AI with Gemini built in

Gemini can help you write, search, summarize, and more all built right intoyour inbox. Use Gemini in Gmail on your computer and on your phone with theofficial Gmail app.

Use Gemini in the side panel<https://c.gle/ANiao5qzCuwbZwtA4SPbVS8Vchmstk40m97lnLtecFLKHIwz6n1d6ChF66CNW1MDcEDW-vEjF2I7gFFBG39IKkGBHgSOjbklgINZAEXmxlDxAMttTahEpsPV1GXMg79d-ykGFjjj9yw9SV74uEvaE2T1DsXiz0nloOhAs9PoIqqy6LEBseHD>

Do more, in less time, with AI

Gemini is your AI-powered productivity partner, built right into GoogleWorkspace. With enterprise-grade data security, Gemini helps you writeemails, analyze documents, translate languages, and more.

column7: 😬 Why You Still Haven’t Started (Yet)
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you've had a good start to the week 🙏

Quick reminder before we start, I’ll be hosting a quarterly
workshop this Saturday (28th June) at 1400 BST where we’ll be
reflecting on the last 90 days and setting our intentions for the
quarter ahead. It's always a fun event so come along if you can,
you can register here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9kkdoi6h9m8n444tnh30xrv/wnh2h6uqv2lg6lfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3N1bW1lci1yZXNldC0yMDI1Lz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bGVhbmxlYXJuaW5nXzIzJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Anyway, today I wanted to share a diagram and a concept from one
of my recent videos.

It’s taken from Pat Flynn’s new book Lean Learning (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9kkdoi6h9m8n444tnh30xrv/reh8h9umvloxzpf6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2xlYW5sZWFybmluZw==
) (great read btw) and I wanted to reshare it because 1) I wish
more people see this diagram and 2) even if you have seen it, I
feel like it’s one of those things that bears repeating
regularly.

So whenever I’m at events or giving talks, I hear a lot of people
say things like, “I want to start a business” or “I want to start
a YouTube channel”, but they’re stuck in this endless cycle of
research. They keep trying to learn more concepts, watch more
videos and consume more content before actually getting started.

And I’ve seen the same pattern play out with people when it comes
to improving their personal productivity too - people consume
endless videos looking for the perfect system or the ideal Notion
set-up without actually taking action.

The thing is, researching and learning feels super productive.
When you watch a YouTube video or read a business book or
whatever, you get this sense of making progress towards doing the
thing. And consuming all this content also makes us feel like
we’re reducing our chance of failure by eliminating the unknown
factors that might trip us up along the way.

(And don’t get me wrong, I’m not immune to this either. I still
have to catch myself regularly too, especially when I'm starting
something new 😅)

But all this consumption doesn’t meaningfully move the needle on
making real progress towards your goals.

Yes, there’s a minimum viable amount of information you need to
get started.

But what a lot of people don’t realise is that it’s actually a
very small amount of information - and way smaller than most
people think, as you can see here in my recreation of Pat’s
diagram:

​
Once you get started, once you’re taking step after step, and
building momentum, that’s when the research and learning becomes
useful, because it’s grounded in action.

The analogy I shared in this video was: to imagine learning how
to ride a bike.

You probably know how to ride one right now, but if you think
about it, there’s a whole bunch of information out there about
bikes that you could theoretically learn - about the gears,
suspension, clip-on-shoe things, foamy bum pads, shorts,
aerodynamics…

But back when you didn’t yet know how to ride, it would have been
completely pointless to consume all the same information that a
Tour de France or Olympic cyclist needs to compete.

Instead, all you needed to do was sit on the bike, maybe use the
training wheels, and just start pedalling. Yep, you may have
fallen off a couple of times, but taking action was the only
thing necessary to learn the skill of riding a bike. And only
once you knew how to ride a bike would it be worth looking into
all the other stuff (if riding bikes is your calling).

So if you’ve ever caught yourself thinking: “Oh if I just consume
more info, then I’ll magically feel ready” remember that
realistically, you’re never going to feel ready. Any new thing
you try to do is always going to involve a little leap of faith.

I hope this was a useful reminder 👌

Have a great week and hope to see some of you at the Summer Reset
(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9kkdoi6h9m8n444tnh30xrv/wnh2h6uqv2lg6lfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3N1bW1lci1yZXNldC0yMDI1Lz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bGVhbmxlYXJuaW5nXzIzJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
) on Saturday 🙌

Ali xx

P.S - if you want to watch the full video, you can do so here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9kkdoi6h9m8n444tnh30xrv/8ghqh3uop679vefl/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9jc1hkU2VEYkRnQT9zaT12b2w0blh3X0JLc3BkYlhF
).

column7: Lovable Update – Agent Mode (Beta), Free Collaboration & More
column9:
Lovable Logo

******************
Lovable Update —
June 2025
******************

Hey,

In the last few weeks we've made some big changes and improvements you should know about!

Check it out:

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Agent Mode (Beta): enabling Lovable to think, plan, and take actions autonomously
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

image

Over the
next couple days we're rolling out Lovable’s Agent Mode to beta, enabling Lovable to think, plan, and take actions autonomously.

Once the mode is available to you, you’ll be able to opt in through settings.

This mode reduces build error rates by 90%, cuts down on unwanted changes, and makes Lovable better at helping you reach your goals.

Lovable's Agent Mode can search your codebase, read files with full context, inspect logs and network activity, search the web in real time, and generate or edit images.

The price for the Agent Mode is usage-based and will depend on the complexity of the prompt.

Read more about the Agent Mode (Beta) and pricing here ( https://lovable.dev/blog/agent-mode-beta ).

Sign up for the livestream on Thursday where we'll go deeper into the Agent Mode here ( https://lu.ma/t3zd2j8r ).

-------------------------
Collaboration is now free
-------------------------

We've made collaboration on Lovable even more accessible by making it a free
feature for all users.

For Free and Pro users:

* Workspace collaboration is now completely free – invite your teammates and start building together at no additional cost.
* Unlocks workspace collaboration for up to 20 members on both Free and Pro plans.
* On Free plans, additional members join as editors; Pro plans offer granular workspace roles and permissions.

For Teams plan users:

* We've simplified our pricing structure and moved you to the Pro plan with significant savings.
* You've been automatically moved from the Teams plan to the Pro plan.
* The Teams plan was 20% more expensive than your current Pro plan, so you'll pay less starting with your next renewal.

All your project and workspace settings remain unchanged.

---------------------
New mobile experience
---------------------

image

We've redesigned the mobile experience for building apps and websites directly from your phone.

You can
now also add Lovable to your dock on iPhone as a PWA.

----------------------------
Find your Projects instantly
----------------------------

image

We've added project search functionality with fuzzy matching by name. Tip: rename your projects for better discoverability.

---------------------------------
Go full-stack on the first prompt
---------------------------------

image

We've rolled out full-stack initial generations to all users, enabling you to connect Supabase before doing an initial generation.

----------------
Enhanced history
view
----------------

image

We've enhanced the history view with a cleaner timeline prioritizing dates, restored versions now visible, and simplified version navigation.

---------
Bug Fixes
---------

* Fixed admin access to integration settings for user projects.
* Resolved issue where admins couldn’t properly access workspaces, causing editor display and functionality issues when visiting team projects.
* Fixed iframe redirect issue that was causing unwanted redirects within the Lovable app.

That's all for now!

Thank you for being a user of Lovable, we're working relentlessly to be able to provide a better experience.

Start Building Now ( https://lovable.dev )

Best,
The Lovable Team

Lovable Logo

Turn ideas into Lovable products at
Lovable.dev ( https://lovable.dev )

Unsubscribe ( http://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgTmjgoDAM-wyQTOsMkEAZfG3lYwlKtkehssQtOoaA== )

column7: Update on Your Application to Serve Robotics
column9:
Hi Candace,

Thank you for your interest in the Sr. Data Analyst role at Serve Robotics. We truly appreciate you taking the time to apply.

At this time, we have filled the position and will not be moving forward with additional candidates. Although we did not have the opportunity to connect during this process, we were grateful for your interest in Serve Robotics and the potential to bring your talents to our team.

We encourage you to stay in touch and consider applying to future opportunities with us. You can always view our open roles at our https://www.serverobotics.com/careers.

Wishing you all the best in your career journey, and we hope to connect with you down the line!

Best regards,
Serve Robotics Recruiting Team

column7: 🔥 Welcome to Visily! 🔥
column9:
Hi Candace Grant!

Welcome to Visily!

We think you're going to love the ability to express your vision with our AI-enhanced wireframing, prototyping, and diagramming tools.

To help you get started, we created 3 daily email tutorials with a short video 🎦 showcasing key features and how easy it is to get started.

So welcome to Day 1! Today's video ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xlRMwr2E9x4 ) is about becoming a Wireframing and Prototyping pro within a few minutes 🔥.

 
Play ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xlRMwr2E9x4 )Try It Now! ( https://app.visily.ai/recent-boards )Here are some of our features that make it easy to create beautiful app designs!

*
Web & Mobile template library ( https://www.visily.ai/templates/ ): Thousands of app screens to accelerate your ideas
*
Smart UI Components ( https://www.visily.ai/component-library/#smart-component ): Full control of content and UX for web and mobile apps
* Screenshot to Design ( https://www.visily.ai/help-center/screenshot-to-wireframe-ai/ ): AI tools to convert screenshots into editable wireframes

(SPOILER ALERT) So here's a spoiler for what's ahead in the next two days.

🚀 Day 2 - Diagrams & Visualization: Sometimes defining your vision involves expressing abstract ideas and processes, right? 

🎁 Day 3 - Special Gift! As a new user, we have a gift waiting for you as a thank you for trying out Visily!

Start exploring, and we’ll see you tomorrow!

Best,

The Visily Team

Visily, AI-powered app wireframing & prototyping

1776 Peachtree St. NW Suite 200N, Atlanta, GA, USA

Facebook ( https://www.facebook.com/visilyai )Instagram ( https://www.instagram.com/visilyai/ )LinkedIn ( https://www.linkedin.com/company/visilyai/ )Twitter ( https://twitter.com/i/flow/login?redirect_after_login=%2Fvisilyai )Visily ( https://www.visily.ai/ )

column7: 👀 Why You NEEED to Learn Storytelling as a Creator
column9:
Hey Candace,

Just a quick thing before we start, we’re now just 5 days away
from launching The 1K Challenge - our 6 week live course helping
you take your first steps on your path to financial freedom. If
this sounds interesting and you want to get updates about the
launch and the product, you can join over 14,000 people and sign
up to the waitlist here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn593mb6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/l2heh6ulz7mvwxbg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1zaW1vbmxhdXJpZV8xNiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

Now, onto today’s email which is actually going to be pretty
short because I want to share some more content with you.

If you read last week’s email, you’ll know that I shared advice
from Simon and Laurie about the 5 things they didn’t do to both
grow their channels to over 150k subscribers, and I appreciate
all the replies that we received too.

And given that people found that useful, I thought I’d share one
of the other key insights from the talk about storytelling,
especially since I get asked about this all the time by my PTYA
students.

Storytelling is one of the most underrated skills when it comes
to growing on YouTube. It’s probably one of the most overlooked
parts of the video creation process (after packaging 😉) but
across the YouTube landscape, every single successful channel
relies on some form of storytelling to create compelling content.
It’s more obvious in some videos, of course, but it’s a skill
that every creator should spend time learning if they want to
create content that drives engagement and channel growth.

Simon and Laurie are both keynote speakers, so they really know
their stuff when it comes to weaving in stories into their videos
and crafting engaging narratives that keep viewers watching and
you can hear exactly how they think about it in this clip that
you can watch below.

-->Watch The Clip Here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn593mb6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/m2h7h6u37z60wlfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2hvdy10by1iZWNvbWUtYS1tYXN0ZXIteW91dHViZS1zdG9yeXRlbGxlci8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9ubGF1cmllXzE2JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
)
Watch The Clip Here (
https://aliabdaal.com/how-to-become-a-master-youtube-storyteller/?utm_source=creatornotes&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=simonlaurie_16
)I hope that was useful, and btw, if you want to be part of these
live sessions and get lifetime access to all our recordings, like
this one, then it’s all included when you join PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn593mb6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/dphehmuemn9wrxtl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9ubGF1cmllXzE2JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
).

(And just a final reminder, if you want to join the 1k Challenge
waitlist, you can do that here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/n4u4z20wxvavhxn593mb6h6pq0kggalhgvoew/l2heh6ulz7mvwxbg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1zaW1vbmxhdXJpZV8xNiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
)).

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: 🧠 Two Small Tweaks To Make Discipline Effortless
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you had a nice weekend 🙌

Some of my old uni friends are visiting Hong Kong this week and
it's been great catching up after not seeing them for so long. As
I mentioned in Feel-Good Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h40nn36alh87dwdkkc4/58hvh8ug08l4kwb7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2Fhd2Vic2l0ZQ==
), people really can be a hidden superpower when it comes to
personal productivity.

But these visits can also create distractions (😬) and so I've
been thinking quite a bit about what I need to do to keep things
moving, especially when it comes to filming.

And that requires discipline, which is what I want to talk about
today because I feel like a lot of people are often missing a few
key things when it comes to thinking about discipline and making
it sustainable.

The thing is, when people say “I wish I were more disciplined,”
what they usually mean is, “I wish I found it easier to do the
things I say I want to do.”

And most of us assume the fix is internal. More willpower. More
motivation. A better morning routine. A more effective way of
focussing. But the truth is, discipline isn’t something you
summon. It’s something you can design for.

I can’t remember where this quote is from (and it’s super simple)
but it sums this up nicely and goes something like this “it
doesn’t take much discipline to avoid eating chocolate if there’s
no chocolate in the house.”

In other words, the easiest way to be disciplined is to make the
undisciplined option less available.

Whenever I do talks or speak to people, I’m often faced with that
question of “how do I get more discipline in my life?” and I
usually start by asking the simple question “what does your
environment look like? Have you designed it to make it way easier
to actually do the thing you want to do?”

And a lot of people haven't stopped to think about that but it's
really one of the simplest ways to follow through on your goals -
reducing what psychologists call environmental friction.

If you want to write more, keep your writing app open by default.
If you want to work out in the morning, lay out your clothes the
night before. If you want to eat healthier, stop stocking your
kitchen with junk.

I know it sounds simple but even I regularly remind myself of
this idea because it’s easy to just assume we’re struggling with
getting something done without really thinking about how our own
environment could be making it harder to achieve our goals.

When I was in med school, I kept my textbooks next to my
desk—because if I had to get up and cross the room to grab them,
I’d probably find something else to do along the way. And these
days, I've got my filming gear permanently set up so that I
'only' need to hit record on my camera when I sit down to film.

Friction matters. Design leads to discipline.

But there’s a second part to this: tracking.

When we measure something, we get clarity. And clarity breeds
consistency. Whether it’s tracking your workouts, your time, or
your progress on a project, simply seeing the data gives you a
feedback loop. It keeps you honest. It’s the visibility which
provides the clarity, accountability and motivation which then
leads to discipline.

So if you’re struggling to be more disciplined, start with these
two questions:

* How can I reduce friction?
* How can I track my progress?

The most sustainable discipline doesn’t come from pushing harder.
It comes from setting things up so the right choice is also the
easy one.

Have a great week ahead!

Ali xx

P.S - if you've realised we're almost five months into 2025 and
you're still looking to get clarity on your goals or you want to
refine your vision or your productivity systems to get back on
track, you might want to check out LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h40nn36alh87dwdkkc4/25h2h9u3gznq45i8/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWRpc2NpcGxpbmVfMjYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==

Hi Candace,

Thank you for your interest in joining us here at Jerry! We have received your application to the Data Scientist position. If you are selected to move forward in our process, someone from our recruiting team will reach out by email with next steps.

For more information about our team and opportunities at Jerry, check out our https://getjerry.com/careers to get the latest updates. Please also note that this inbox is not monitored, please do not respond to this email directly.

The Jerry Team

 SECURE YOUR FUTURE: SHARE YOUR CERTIFICATES
When you add your IxDF Membership Certificate to your LinkedIn profile,
resumé/CV, website/blog, and portfolio, you don't just showcase your skills—you 
safeguard your future:

 1. You build your brand as a forward-thinking professional ready to upskill
    yourself before others.
 2. You show off your new skills so you don't get left behind when managers
    decide who to reward and promote.
 3. You attract new opportunities and collaborations with decision-makers.

column7: [Next week] Is your data team building with AI-ready data?
column9:
Join us on August 19th at 10 AM PT as we talk to Sam Garfield, Analytics Engineer at Retool, about the messy reality of making data work for AI—and the practical steps that actually move

Data Eng Webinar_Email header_1600 x 600 (https://events.retool.com/data-holding-back-your-ai?utm_source=hs_email&utm_medium=email&rcid=701Qo000011xQAPIA2&_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8tD56jmW2I2iBNb0yljji0mpULJtGmyHp-iZcuDkpceT_Z-N2qhughOIMUsCHz7xM-05kDNG63wbtpy9QdOcyEWIqN8g&_hsmi=375875869 )

Hi Candace,

Most organizations have the LLM part of AI implementation figured out. The real challenge is building AI systems that can reliably access the right data, make decisions based on complete context, and take action without creating new problems.

Next week, we're sitting down with Sam Garfield, Analytics Engineer, for a candid conversation about the messy reality of making data work for AI—and the practical steps that actually move the needle.

REGISTER NOW
(https://events.retool.com/data-holding-back-your-ai?utm_source=hs_email&utm_medium=email&rcid=701Qo000011xQAPIA2&_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8tD56jmW2I2iBNb0yljji0mpULJtGmyHp-iZcuDkpceT_Z-N2qhughOIMUsCHz7xM-05kDNG63wbtpy9QdOcyEWIqN8g&_hsmi=375875869 )

During the webinar, you'll learn:

- The data connection problem everyone’s dealing with—why scattered sources leave AI making decisions with half the story, and what's actually working to fix it
- Quality control that doesn’t slow you down—Sam’s take on keeping AI agents reliable without drowning your team in monitoring systems
- Why most unstructured data breaks AI systems and the unglamorous work that actually makes logs, docs, and conversations useful for LLMs
- Real stories of teams automating sales qualification, chargeback defense, and support routing (including what didn’t work the first time)

Whether you’re a data engineer future-proofing your stack or a technical leader mapping your AI strategy, you'll come away with practical insights for making your data truly AI-ready.

Can't make it? Register anyway, and we'll send you the recording.

Best,

The Retool team

“OH MY GOSH, I LOVE …”
By Mia Leimkuhler

Hello! Mia here, filling in for Emily today. Always a pleasure.

I often feel shy and awkward at parties, so I’m grateful that my job makes such
an easy conversation starter. Tell people you work at New York Times Cooking and
they’ll immediately ask you for recipe recommendations, cooking tips and what
Melissa Clark is like in person. (In that order: Start with our Weeknight 100

They’ll also volunteer their favorite NYT Cooking recipe, which always brings me
joy. I had someone corner me at a party to tell me how much he adores Hetty Lui
McKinnon’s sheet-pan pierogies with brussels sprouts and kimchi

. I’m pretty sure he used the words “brilliant” and “life-changing,” or at least

So today’s weeknight quintet is a gathering of recipes that have been
enthusiastically recommended to me by other NYT Cooking cookers, with two that I
always trot out for that “Any favorites?” question. Enjoy!

Whenever he visits me, my brother requests “that pasta with the green sauce.”
This is that pasta with the green sauce, a recipe by Joshua McFadden adapted by
Tejal Rao. The green part comes from a pound of blanched kale blended with
sizzled garlic; I’ve used regular green kale instead of lacinato nearly every
time (because that’s what my corner store carries) and it always turns out
wonderfully.

[HTTPS://NL.NYTIMES.COM/F/COOKING/ENCTPARFHGUNKXIIJ42T6Q~~/AAAAARA~/X6YKIW-GI7GUT6UWQHCXRZ6BYSSCC23ULJP00NBI7KMBXCUDDAE00KKSUEPV1ZKEJQX_3OTLF6UEFSDKT-0XU0WNTIYSDYWWYIE6GGJDKWSCV-OTRMKSBKPIUGD_0SG0HWNQTL61TVFWJ_EMCJ3VYPHBVLFTZSVCSX76ZFPZXEXVSQ1L_8EFW71VUHN-IYVD3QWSJZ3MS8FVPXP5IUAUQ5XIAK45QT_YR_FYM4TUS1RT4HJZQUBDPBVL94FXLHSLNETASO_KIEM2FODIDELVK-QAEZNRTF0RDUW7U8THVJPRV6QYYT2ZSTF78YX9X3QGXI4Q6ULJIJMQDTRHLXMSCPKQFKEP_HZSUFJJJXGIJRWWLZWHGO0LKDG0OAT7AT6TE4MVXO_OA_FI6CRRHXVWH9WQ8-BXG95XMR9MBOQG_BU~]
Are you tired of hot honey yet? Good, me neither. I love this simple, 30-minute
Ali Slagle supper and recommend it to anyone who needs a go-to chicken dish with
the vegetable element built in. Make it as spicy — or not spicy — as you like by
scaling the chile up or down, and play with your greens. I crave the slightly
bitter edge escarole provides, but you might prefer chard, mustard greens or
kale. This is one of those dinners that, with a glass of wine, feels almost too
nice for a weeknight.

And let’s end where we started, on a sheet-pan stunner. Longtime readers know
and love this Eric Kim classic, and it’s a perfect “Welcome to NYT Cooking”
recipe: versatile, clever, delicious, easy. This is the recipe I suggest to
anyone who needs a good clean-out-the-fridge option. I can’t think of a better
way to use up one sweet potato, an onion, some kale (or broccoli or green beans
or brussels sprouts) and leftover rice. (I’ve tried it with all of those
vegetables, by the way. All great.)

column7: Final weeks: Submit your mobile app and win $5K
column9:
Don't wait: Enter your app today







Hi Bubbler,



Quick reminder: There are less than four weeks left in the Bubble Summer 
Mobile App Challenge <https://bubble.io/c/mobile-summer-hackathon> — don't miss 
your chance to win up to$5,000 by building and publishing a native mobile app!



Resources:


 * Seasoned Bubble dev? Check out this deep dive on web vs. mobile development 
→ <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UulExKeOLuc>
 * Brand new to Bubble? Watch our Getting Started course →  
<https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLoNVJrdvQQYmLlrIP-sQg0oJGf6V298y8>
 * Ready to deploy? Read the overview here and don’t forget to check the iOS 
and Android guides → 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app>
 * For some inspiration, here’s the incredible mobile app that developer James 
Devonport built for Create With in just one week → 
<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N5t3l4zQrwQ> 

⏰ Challenge ends August 18, 2025



Here's what you need to know if you're planning to participate:



📱 Don’t miss the deadline 
 App store approvals can take up to two weeks on both iOS and Android. Submit 
by early August to make the deadline.



🏆 What you can win


 * 
$5,000 cash for the top new iOS app

 * $5,000 cash for the top new Android app
 *  $5,000 cash for a standout companion mobile app to an existing web app

Note: The same person cannot win across multiple categories.



A quick reminder on how to enter:


 * 
Build: Use Bubble's native mobile tools to build an app (any apps started on 
or afterJune 17, 2025 are eligible)

 * Publish: Once you're ready to deploy, submit this form 
<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdvOmijB_9HAYsvN0zXFE8xm8ZTh_tgcZOl5OQPsum1aYXEiQ/viewform?usp=sharing&ouid=100978906137280298323>
 to get one month of Bubble's Starter plan for free. Then publish your app on 
the App Store or Google Play by August 18. The first 1,000 submissions will be 
sent to the judges!
 * Share: Post final demo video on X and LinkedIn with #BubbleMobileChallenge. 

Keep an eye out: We’ll announce winners at the end of August! (Beta or 
Testflight submissions are not eligible for prizes.)



 Apps will be judged by our expert panel (including Karthik “KP” Puvadda 
<https://www.linkedin.com/in/karthikpuvvada/>, Founder Relations at Paddle, 
Wayne Hu <https://www.linkedin.com/in/wayne-hu-05570132/>, Partner at 
SignalFire, andLisa Michelle <https://www.linkedin.com/in/lisamichellet/>, 
Founder at Durag Fest) onvisual/UI quality, scale potential, and ability to 
solve real user problems. 



Time to get building! We're excited to see what you create.



Team Bubble





 <https://bubble.io/> 

You’re getting this email because you’re building an app with Bubble. 
If it looks weird, view it in your browser 
<https://links.bubble.io/s/vb/u8MFmB46wmDz3EBkxn-R-FrVKqHpCRF017hzg6MW1ij1GWOUglWc1yte9zedzTUpeE1kH2NNNBZaqg_DtGj-A4XhDjPn7xnal8zNb_wEJ1G4h-70YC-mS0uff6OR5_yaNyVsFx14JRu6zeRAMYY/ehjRyNjGqWn6icM1P20nP1QE1kpE3YaF/11>
.



Not interested in emails like this?

Stop receiving messages of this type

column7: Principal Data Scientist I – Let’s get started!
Break the negative thought cycle
column9:
Candace...

 

Last week I send you my new Youtube video on 7 ways to break the cycle of negative thoughts...

 

But there was something I missed.

 

And I didn't realize it until I heard Virla's video message this morning.

 

She's one of our students graduating as a certified coach from the Jay Shetty Certification School ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-negative-cycle-171-1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+171-1&utm_content_name=Break+the+negative+thought+cycle&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) this Wednesday... and her story hit me right in the heart.

 

Since she was a little girl, Virla had been stuck in a cycle that felt impossible to break:

 

❌ Never feeling good enough.

 

❌ Never feeling she had anything to offer.

 

❌ Never feeling worthy.

 

No matter what she tried…

 

Nothing seemed to shift that weight she carried.

 

It started feeling like maybe this was just... it.

 

Just how life would always be.

 

Then she heard me speaking…

 

And something in my words sparked a light inside her…

 

That said “Coaching is the path you need.”

 

 

Now, 6 months later, she’s made the mindset switch she’s been searching for her entire life.

 

The heaviness that was weighing her down? Gone.

 

She feels lighter. 

 

Happier.

 

Free.

 

And most importantly…

 

She’s using what she’s learned to help others as a powerful Mindset Coach.

 

So her clients can help others create the same transformation in their own minds.

 

And live their happiest lives with Virla’s guidance.

 

 

If you’ve been searching for a way to turn your challenges into real, meaningful change for others.

 

I've got a new group of coaching students enrolling right now...

 

Click here to learn more about my school and how it could change your life. ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/c2c-video-bau-e/?el=C2C-email-negative-cycle-171-1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+171-1&utm_content_name=Break+the+negative+thought+cycle&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

* Run your first workflow

column7: ✅ investor requests
column9:
This email provides you a list of what our investors are allocating into right now**Investor Mandates: **Last week we had the Chief Investment Officer of a $30 Billion family office at our workshops, along with multiple investors who have had $50M and $100M exits.  We also heard from a member who closed their $5 Million round in 72 hours.

Through connecting with those investors about our July 15th Hawaii Family Office Retreat and in-person artificial intelligence implementation bootcamps coming up in August in 4 cities, here is an updated list of what investment opportunities they are asking us for right now:

* 

**Data Centers**: Few investors know how to invest in this space, yet they hear of it scaling exponentially right now.

* 

**10+ Year Trade Companies**: Think pool cleaners, electricians, HVAC, plumbers, etc.  Family run businesses, those making $1-$2M+ in profits have been approached 100+ times already.  For those reasons several investors I know are looking at $500k-$1M in profits companies in this area.

* 

**Solar**: Companies that do not rely on tax credits to thrive, and have a long-term well-established service, installation business, or tech that has traction are of interest.

* 

**Healthcare/Medical Practice Investments**: Most investors never get to invest in multi-location medical practices with 1,000's of patients per location.  The most in-demand areas are dermatology, oncology, obstetrician/birthing centers, and dentistry.  

* 

**Land Development**:  Investors are allocating to gold, crypto, land for security, an inflation hedge and store of value.  Properties with a lot of land, some small cash flow and the ability to segment off parts of the asset to lower their cost basis are of interest to many investors. 

* 

**Revenue Positive AI Platforms**: There are so many AI companies now that sorting out who to trust, believe, and invest in is hard.  Those who meet in-person, who pitch those who have operated in their niche, or who have a clear demonstrable value-add a non techy will have a big edge.

* 

**Storage & Mobile Home Parks**: We find investors do not see a lot of opportunities in these areas, especially MHP.  When there is a clear value-add play it typically is easier to close vs. a ground up construction project it seems.

* 

**AI Infrastructure:**Companies that will scale as AI scales, regardless of which AI company takes the throne in any of the 500 niches the 80,000 AI companies out there are trying to be #1 in

* 

**Income Investments:**Investors want sleep-at-night income properties backed by collateral or a secure platform

* 

**Multifamily**: Simple to understand forced appreciation plays, adding ADUs, converting X into additional units, 3.75% interest rate or lower assumable debt, etc.

* 

**Technology**: Investors are pitched on technology investments often these days, so those who win the allocation are those who they trust, understand their value-add process and have met in-person typically

* 

**Energy**: Already cash flowing energy saving devices, profitable companies, or oil and gas businesses near where they reside 

* 

**Recurring Revenue: ** Stable subscription-based companies are in high demand like usual, but investors are fearful of overpaying due to SaaS multiples typically being sky high.

If you want to learn more about our investor club that hosts 22 live, in-person events annually, please see our event schedule, investor data sets, AI tools, speaking opportunities, and more here: https://FamilyOffices.com https://familyoffices.com

Richard C. Wilson

CEO & Founder

column7: Build your own Deep Agent – New Academy Course
column9:
Learn to build agents for complex, long-running tasks

Many agents today follow the same simple pattern: run in a loop, call tools. That architecture works well enough, but it breaks down as tasks get more complex. These agents often struggle to plan over longer horizons or manage more demanding workflows.

Major model providers have built “deep” agents in domains like coding and research. These agents dive deeper – they’re able to plan complex tasks and carry them out over longer time horizons.

Today, companies of all sizes – from startups to large enterprises – are building their own Deep Agents.

There are four key features that set Deep Agents apart from regular agents:

- Planning – keeps agents on track
- File system – allows agents to offload context
- Sub-agents – act as focused specialists
- Prompting – provides agents with detailed instructions

Our latest LangChain Academy course, Deep Agents with LangGraph, shows you how to combine these pieces with LangGraph to orchestrate long-running, multi-agent workflows.

By the end, you’ll have the skills to design, implement, and deploy your own Deep Agent – ready to tackle complex, long-running tasks in your domain.

column7: The 10-minute test that reveals if you'll ever learn Python (scary accurate)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Last week I told you about our Python for Beginners live course.

Maybe you thought about signing up for an info session. Maybe you didn't.

Either way, I'm about to save you months of wasted time with a simple test.

Ready? Here goes:

Think about the last time you tried to learn something new online.

Maybe it was Python. Maybe Excel. Maybe bread baking. Doesn't matter.

Here's what I've noticed after talking to hundreds of learners:

Did you quit because the material was too hard? Or because you were alone with a screen and zero accountability?

For 9 out of 10 people, it's that second one. The isolation. The confusion about what to learn next. The midnight error messages with nobody to ask.

Here's the brutal truth about learning Python:

The code isn't hard. Variables aren't hard. Loops aren't hard. Even object-oriented programming isn't hard.

You
know what's hard?

Sitting alone at 9 PM, staring at an error message, with nobody to ask for help. Opening YouTube and seeing 847 different tutorials, all teaching different things. Having no idea if you're learning the right stuff in the right order.

THAT'S what's hard.

And that's exactly why most people have a folder called "Python_Learning" with 14 half-finished projects from 2023.

So here's what I'm proposing:

Before you waste another evening googling "best way to learn Python 2025" (which brought you here, didn't it?), spend 60 minutes finding out if structured learning is your missing piece.

Our info sessions aren't webinars. They're not sales pitches with 45 minutes of "my journey" stories.

They're demonstrations.

Stephen Gruppetta will literally teach you something about Python in the session. Right there. Live.

You'll see exactly how he breaks down concepts. How he answers questions. How the
daily structure works. How the live sessions run.

In 60 minutes, you'll know if this clicks with your brain or not.

Here's what past participants discovered in their info sessions:

"I realized I wasn't stupid. I just needed someone to explain the WHY, not just the HOW."

"After 10 minutes, I understood something that 6 YouTube videos couldn't explain."

"I finally saw how all the pieces connect instead of random fragments."

The course starts October 13th. These info sessions are your only chance to see if this is your path forward.

Still available:

* Fri, Sep 26 → [Register] ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners-info-sessions/ )
* Wed, Oct 8 → [Register] ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners-info-sessions/ )
But here's what I really want you to understand...

Every day you delay is another day you're the person who "wants to learn Python" instead of the person who "knows Python."

And that gap? It's costing you.

Not just money (though Python developers aren't exactly struggling). It's costing you opportunities. Projects. Confidence. The ability to build that idea you've been sitting on.

Six months from now, you'll either be writing Python with confidence, or you'll be reading another email like this, still "planning to start soon."

The info session is free. ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners-info-sessions/ ) It's 60 minutes. And it might be the difference between another year of tutorials and actually becoming someone who codes.

See you there. ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners-info-sessions/ )

— Dan Bader

P.S. You know what the most successful students have in common? They stopped researching and started doing. They picked a path and committed. The info session isn't about research. It's about recognizing if this is YOUR path.

P.P.S. Warning: Stephen might make you write actual code during the info session. Not copy code. Not watch him code. Write it yourself. If that terrifies you, good. That's the feeling of real learning about to happen.

P.P.P.S. "But what if I'm too busy?" Here's the thing: busy people learn Python all the time. They just stop waiting for the "perfect time" (spoiler: it never comes). If 60 minutes feels impossible, then yeah, maybe Python isn't happening this year. But if you can find 60 minutes to see if this could work? That's how transformational change actually starts.

To make sure you keep getting these emails, please add info@realpython.com to your address book or allowlist. Want out of the loop? Unsubscribe ( https://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgSUzQcDAKymeaumeQGZdv2aZVZPWmTe3mXnFfM= )

Our postal address: #720-999 West Broadway, Vancouver BC V5Z 1K5, Canada

Exciting news!

We're hosting another Prompt Your Way To Profit Masterclass this month!

Why?

Because tons of people reached out to us last time, saying they couldn't make it live or that they'd like to see it again.

So if you didn't make it last month or you want a refresher, I'd love to have you!

We're going live next Tuesday, September 23rd, at 9 AM PST.

Here's what I'll cover:

Prompt Your Way To Profit: Discover The 4 Prompts Freelance Writers Are Using Right Now To Make $100,000+ Per Year

In this Masterclass, I'll cover the 4 pillars of becoming an AI ghostwriter:

• Pillar #1: Positioning - Why you shouldn’t call yourself a “freelance writer” anymore, and how to position yourself as a Premium Ghostwriter instead.

• Pillar #2: Packaging - How to stop charging per word, or per hour, and instead charge a premium by selling a repeatable, productized service.

• Pillar #3: Outreach - How to find warm & cold clients, identify problems you can help them solve, and reach out to them (without being sales-y).

• Pillar #4: Fulfillment - How to use AI to do 80% of the work. Whether you’re ghostwriting short-form social content, weekly newsletters, or social media management and engagement.

And we will show you our exact AI prompts to help you implement all of this 10x faster.

Plus, when you attend live, I’ll share a free gift with you, too!

(But you have to register AND attend live to get it!)

Click here to claim your free spot.

Chat soon,

Cole

P.S. Can't make it live?

column7: This could be you by Halloween
column9:
“There must be something more”

 

“I’m capable of more”

 

“But how do I get there?”

 

These are the questions that brought my latest graduate, Kori, to my Certification School for aspiring coaches.

 

What she saw - our mission, our values, our principles - connected with her on a deeper level than anything else.

 

And it only got better once she got inside.

 

Over the months, she used everything she learned about coaching to connect with herself, with others in her life, and her new purpose as a coach.

 

And, as of yesterday, Kori is ready to start living that purpose.

 

She’s just graduated from the school.

 

Ready to start helping her clients connect and build stronger relationships - as a newly-certified Relationship & Connection Coach.

 

Now…

 

We’re enrolling a new cohort of students who want to follow in Kori’s footsteps - and become a certified coach by Halloween.

 

If you want to hear more about what we stand for as a school…

 

And learn if this could be the next chapter FOR YOU too:

 

Click here and watch this video → ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-could-be-you-171-7&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+171-7&utm_content_name=This+could+be+you+by+Halloween&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

column7: 12,168 Python Learners Reported the Same Problem. We Fixed It.
column9:
( https://realpython.com/ )

Hi Candace,

Good news, there are new notifications & updates waiting for you in your Real Python account. Here’s what you may have missed:

Announcement
------------

--------------------------------------------------------------
12,168 Python Learners Reported the Same Problem. We Fixed It.
--------------------------------------------------------------

( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners/?utm_source=notification_summary&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=2025-09-29 )

After surveying thousands of beginners, we discovered something troubling: Many can follow tutorials perfectly but freeze when facing a blank file.

Sound familiar?

Our new 8-week cohort course tackles this “Builder’s Gap” head-on. Instead of memorizing syntax, you’ll learn to think in code through live instruction with Stephen Gruppetta (PhD, Real Python Core Team).

Limited to 10 students per group. Direct feedback on your actual code. No TAs, no chatbots. Stephen himself guides you from zero to building real programs.

Course runs Oct 13–Dec 5. Registration closes soon.

See the Full Syllabus and Reserve Your Spot » ( https://realpython.com/workshops/python-for-beginners/?utm_source=notification_summary&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=2025-09-29 )

column7: 🙌 Why You Should Start a YouTube Channel (Even if No One Watches)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Quick note before we begin - we’re hosting our usual quarterly
workshop on Saturday 28th June at 1400 BST to help you set
yourself up for success moving into July and beyond. We always
get great feedback from these events so if you’re keen on
joining, you can sign up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/7qh7h2u9p9vnoet9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3N1bW1lci1yZXNldC0yMDI1Lz9sbS1nYQ==
).

Hope you've had a good start to the week. Apologies that this is
coming a day late - the website was down yesterday which was
slightly frustrating 😬

And the website isn't the only thing that's been disrupted
either. Filming was interrupted again at home last week -
honestly, just when I start to get on a roll with 2 videos per
week, building work starts next door so I’ve had to move to a
local co-working space to film which is not ideal.

Sometimes you’ve just got to adapt to keep the production ball
rolling 😅

Anyway, over the past couple of weeks one of my recent videos
about YouTube (Why Everyone Should Start a YouTube Channel (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/owhkhwuwlw3qrzcq/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9NUEVDRHVPVUJFWT9zaT1wdEM5TjZaUWYxZmpGd1Nv
)) has started to pick up after we made a change to the thumbnail
(I've been telling you that packaging matters 😉) but it got me
reflecting again on the reasons holding people back from starting
their own channels.

Obviously there’s a whole host of reasons that I’ve heard over
the years from audience members or friends looking to start a
YouTube channel but one of the more common concerns I see is that
people are just conscious of being ‘bad’ at something and,
understandably, we tend to shy away from that feeling.

And it’s not just on YouTube. When we think about learning to
play a musical instrument, picking up a new sport - many of us
hit a massive roadblock because we don’t want to put ourselves
through the discomfort of being bad at something again.

But here’s the truth: you can’t learn anything new without first
being okay with being bad at it.

There’s no shortcut—you have to go through a phase when you
completely suck at it, because that’s where the real growth
happens.

Unlike jumping on a Zoom call or simply responding to a question
someone asks you in real life, picking up your phone and hitting
record to film your first ever YouTube video feels completely
different.

The thought of posting it on the internet stirs up a pot of
wildly different emotions, because you’re putting your ego in a
vulnerable place where it could be judged—and that’s scary for a
lot of people.

But it’s also incredibly powerful.

You’ll feel fear, judgment, and discomfort. You’ll worry about
what others might think about your appearance, your voice, or
what you’re saying. And you’ll have no other choice but to face
your inner demons.

But personal growth is all about willingly putting yourself in
uncomfortable situations, and when you start a YouTube channel
you’re doing exactly that.

You’ll also have to trust me when I say that people don’t care
nearly half as much as you think.

And even if they do, it really shouldn’t matter—because part of
adopting a growth mindset is all about learning how to stop
living by other people’s opinions.

I’ve seen so many people join PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/z2hgh7uere9le9iz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWRpc2NvbWZvcnRfMTEmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) and only make a handful of videos, yet they still say the
experience of learning a new skill was totally worth it. Even
though they didn’t become full-time YouTubers, which was perhaps
their goal to begin with, the confidence and emotional resilience
they built through simply starting—and sucking—was genuinely
life-changing.

So, if you’re on the fence about launching your own YouTube
channel, I want you to focus on the real reward that comes from
confronting those things blocking you from hitting record. It’s
incredibly valuable to understand these feelings exist, figure
out where they come from, and move through them, because you’ll
come out much stronger on the other side.

And if you want to lean into that discomfort and take that first
step, you can join the Part-Time YouTuber Academy here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/z2hgh7uere9le9iz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWRpc2NvbWZvcnRfMTEmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) or, if you don't want to commit to the full programme, you can
take on the 7 Video Challenge to kickstart your journey here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/p8hehqu454kq43ur/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249ZGlzY29tZm9ydF8xMSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

I’d love to hear how if felt when you filmed your first ever
video—so hit reply and let me know. 😉

And I’ll see you next week!

Ali xx

🚀 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/d0ugqd98lob0ho74vl2hmhzp70444flhogk0v/x0hph3uede8qeptg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
).

Update Your Email Preferences (
